# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aaron-cicourel
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aaron-cicourel/aaron-cicourel] In November 2007, he was awarded Docteur Honoris Causa by Université de Fribourg in Switzerland, and in 2008 was awarded Doctor Honoris Causa Complutense University of Madrid.
[src:aaron-cicourel/aaron-cicourel] Cicourel was elected Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and of the American Association for the Advancement of Science.
[src:aaron-cicourel/aaron-cicourel] Cicourel was likely the first scholar to use the full name of "British Sign Language" in an academic publication.
[src:aaron-cicourel/aaron-cicourel] Aaron Cicourel died on July 22, 2023, at the age of 94.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] Schutz was born on 13 April 1899 in Vienna, Austria, as the only child in an upper-middle-class Jewish family.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] Following his graduation from high school, he was drafted into the Austrian Army where he quickly rose to the American equivalent rank of second lieutenant.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] His army regiment was dispatched to fight in a series of heavy battles on the Italian front (WWI).
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] In 1918, Schutz enrolled at the University of Vienna, where he earned his law degree.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] He also enrolled at the Viennese Academy of International Trade from 1919 to 1920, specialising in international law.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] During his time at the University of Vienna, attending lectures given by Max Weber, Schutz came to the conclusion that Weber had left the problem of *meaning* unexplicated.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] As noted by Helmut Wagner (1983), Schutz's fascination with this problem was a result of his experience in combat, combined with returning to starving and economically decimated Vienna.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] Partly because there were few academic posts available, he developed a well-established and prominent career in international banking, He became the chief financial officer for Reitler and Company, the Vienna banking firm.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] His academic work was done in his spare time.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] He was once described by Edmund Husserl as "a banker by day and a philosopher by night." In 1933, the threat of Adolf Hitler's rise in Germany caused Schutz and other Viennese intellectuals to flee Austria and seek asylum in allied countries.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] Schutz and his family relocated to Paris in 1938 in political exile.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] He continued to work for Reitler and Company as an international lawyer.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] He moved to the United States in 1939, where he became a part-time faculty member of The New School.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] There, he taught sociology and philosophy, as well as serving as chair of the Philosophy department.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] Schutz received a substantial amount of assistance from his wife, Ilse, who transcribed his working notes and letters from his taped dictations.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] Schutz died on 20 May 1959 in New York City at the age of 60.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] Four volumes of Collected Papers were published posthumously, along with the draft of a second book he had been working on prior to his death.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] Schutz was strongly influenced by Ludwig von Mises, Henri Bergson, William James, and Edmund Husserl, as well as Max Weber.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] Drawing on phenomenology, Schutz's principal aim was to create a philosophical foundation for the social sciences.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] While Schutz's work paralleled George Herbert Mead’s analysis of the meanings within social interactions, Schutz was highly critical of Mead’s behavioristic approach.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] Although Schutz was never a student of Husserl, he and colleague Felix Kaufmann intensively studied Husserl's work in order to seek a basis for Weber's interpretive sociology and for Austrian economic theory.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] In 1932, Schutz’s efforts resulted in his first published book, *Der sinnhafte Aufbau der sozialen Welt* ('The Meaningful Structure of the Social World') which was published in English as *The Phenomenology of the Social World*.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] Schutz argues that social science must be grounded in analysis of what Husserl referred to as 'the natural attitude', the assumptions that structure everyday perceptions and actions in the social world.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] Schutz retains Weber's conception of social science as properly committed to the principle of value neutrality, but also to value relevance, and that its investigations must rely on “ideal types”.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] He viewed the technique of bracketing, drawn from Husserlian phenomenology, as a way beyond the limitations of ideal-type analysis.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] This publication brought him to the attention of Husserl, whom he visited frequently and corresponded with until Husserl's death in 1938.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] Even so, when Husserl asked Schutz to be his assistant, he was unable to accept the offer at Freiburg University for personal reasons.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] Schutz's main area of concern was the ways in which people grasp the consciousness of others while living within their own streams of consciousness.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] He spoke much about intersubjectivity, in a broader sense, using it in reference to the social world, specifically the social nature of knowledge.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] A great deal of his work deals with the "lifeworld," in which people create social reality under the constraints of preexisting social and cultural factors and structures.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] Schutz is also known for his belief that humans attempt to typify everything; i.e., to categorize people and things to better understand them within the context of society.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] He believed that the various typifications we use inform how we understand and interact with people and objects in the social world.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] Schutz's theories and conceptions are illuminated through an intense and insightful correspondence with Harvard scholar Talcott Parsons.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] The thrust of the discussion centered on the meaning of the concept "social action." Whether the Schutz-Parsons correspondence can be characterized as “dialogue” rather than “debate” has been analyzed by Rehorick (1980).
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] Further insights into the fundamental differences between Schutz and Parsons is provided by a critical examination of original correspondence that brought in a third scholarly voice—that of Eric Voegelin.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] This discussion shows that conceptual and theoretical differences between Schutz and Parsons stem from different “ways of knowing,” implying fundamentally different orientations toward social scientific thought.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] Schutz's writings have had a lasting impact on the social sciences, both on phenomenological approaches to sociology and in ethnomethodology (through the writings of Harold Garfinkel).
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] Heavily influenced by Schutz's work as his student, Thomas Luckmann ultimately finished Schutz's work on the structures of the lifeworld by filling out his unfinished notes after Schutz died.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] Berger and Luckmann went on to use Schutz's work to further understand human culture and reality, through the development of a new form of the sociology of knowledge.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] Phenomenology is the study of things as they appear (i.e., *phenomena*).
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] Phenomenology originated with Edmund Husserl, who Schutz studied and even met.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] There are many assumptions behind phenomenology that help explain its creation.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] First, it rejects the concept of objective research: phenomenologists would rather group presumptions through a process called *phenomenological epoche*.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] Second, phenomenology believes that analyzing the daily human behavior will provide one with a comprehensive understanding of nature.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] The third assumption is that persons, not individuals, should be explored and questioned.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] Sociologically speaking, this is in part because persons can be better understood by the unique ways they reflect and symbolize the society they live in.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] Fourth, phenomenologists prefer to gather *capta*, or *conscious experience*, rather than traditional data.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] Finally, phenomenology is considered to be oriented on discovery, and therefore phenomenologists gather research using methods that are far less restricting than in other sciences.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] Social phenomenology is concerned with how people use ordinary, everyday interactions to produce a feeling of reality and intersubjectivity.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] Most of Schutz's work concerned the methods used for the construction of reality through everyday experiences.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] The social construction of reality and ethnomethodology are disciplinary extensions beyond the social phenomenology of Alfred Schutz.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] As noted by Farganis (2011), phenomenological sociology is characterized as particularly subjective in nature because its emphasis of understanding reality through the perspective of the acting subject rather than through the lens of the scientific observer.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] There is this existence of meaning that comes into play, yet most people simply accept the world how it is and never second guess the concept or problem of meaning.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] Schutz delves even more into specific relationships such as the difference between intimate face-to-face relationships and distant and impersonal relationships.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] Schutz's division of Husserl's *lebenswelt* (the mundane 'lifeworld') into four distinct sub-worlds is perhaps his most influential theoretical contribution.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] 2. social reality that is on the horizon of direct experience.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] The former consists of the *umwelt* ('environment'), the environment defined through the perception and action of agents.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] 3. the world of successors (*folgewelt*).
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] The last two represent the past and the future, whereas one's contemporaries share a community of time, if not space, and are different from the predecessors and successors because it is possible for them to become fellow-men or consociates.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] Schutz was interested in documenting the transition from direct to indirect experience and the series of experiences in between.
[src:aaron-cicourel/alfred-schutz] In his later writings, Schutz explored how everyday social experiences that pertain to these dimensions are most often intertwined in varying degrees of anonymity.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The **American Academy of Arts and Sciences** (**The Academy**) is one of the oldest learned societies in the United States.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It was founded in 1780 during the American Revolution by John Adams, John Hancock, James Bowdoin, Andrew Oliver, and other Founding Fathers of the United States.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It is headquartered in Cambridge, Massachusetts.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Membership in the academy is achieved through a nominating petition, review, and election process.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The academy's quarterly journal, *Dædalus*, is published by the MIT Press on behalf of the academy, and has been open-access since January 2021.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The academy also conducts multidisciplinary public policy research.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Patton has served as President of the Academy since January 2025.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The first class of new members, chosen by the Academy in 1781, included Benjamin Franklin and George Washington as well as several international honorary members.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The initial volume of Academy *Memoirs* appeared in 1785, and the *Proceedings* followed in 1846.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the 1950s, the Academy launched its journal *Daedalus*, reflecting its commitment to a broader intellectual and socially-oriented program.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Since the second half of the twentieth century, independent research has become a central focus of the Academy.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the late 1950s, arms control emerged as one of its signature concerns.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The Academy also served as the catalyst in establishing the National Humanities Center in North Carolina.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the late 1990s, the Academy developed a new strategic plan, focusing on four major areas: science, technology, and global security; social policy and education; humanities and culture; and education.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In 2002, the Academy established a visiting scholars program in association with Harvard University.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] More than 75 academic institutions from across the country have become Affiliates of the Academy to support this program and other Academy initiatives.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The Academy has sponsored a number of awards and prizes, throughout its history and has offered opportunities for fellowships and visiting scholars at the Academy.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In July 2013, *The Boston Globe* exposed then president Leslie Berlowitz for falsifying her credentials, faking a doctorate, and consistently mistreating her staff.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It is modeled on the Science and Engineering Indicators, published biennially by the National Science Board as required by Congress.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Ever since the founding of the Academy, its members have been nominated and elected by peers.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Members of the Academy included not only scientists and scholars, but also writers and artists as well as representatives from the full range of professions and public life.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Throughout the Academy's history, more than 10,000 fellows have been elected.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Astronomer Maria Mitchell was the first woman elected to the Academy, in 1848.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The current membership encompasses over 5,700 members based across the United States and around the world.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Academy members include more than 250 Nobel laureates and more than 60 Pulitzer Prize winners.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Of the Academy's 14,343 members since 1780, 1,406 are or have been affiliated with Harvard University, 611 with the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, 433 with Yale University, 425 with the University of California, Berkeley, and 404 with Stanford University.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The following table includes those institutions affiliated with 300 or more members.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] † Excludes members affiliated exclusively with associated national laboratories.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] As of 2023, membership is divided into five classes and thirty specialties.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] AAAS was the first permanent organization established to promote science and engineering nationally and to represent the interests of American researchers from across all scientific fields.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] It is the world's largest general scientific society, with over 120,000 members, and is the publisher of the well-known scientific journal *Science*.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The American Association for the Advancement of Science was created on September 20, 1848, at the Academy of Natural Sciences in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] According to the first constitution which was agreed to at the September 20 meeting, the goal of the society was to promote scientific dialogue in order to allow for greater scientific collaboration.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] By doing so, the association aimed to use resources to conduct science with increased efficiency and allow for scientific progress at a greater rate.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The association also sought to increase the resources available to the scientific community through active advocacy of science.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] There were only 78 members when the AAAS was formed.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] As a member of the new scientific body, Matthew Fontaine Maury, USN was one of those who attended the first 1848 meeting.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] At a meeting held on Friday afternoon, September 22, 1848, Redfield presided, and Matthew Fontaine Maury gave a full scientific report on his *Wind and Current Charts*.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Maury stated that hundreds of ship navigators were now sending abstract logs of their voyages to the United States Naval Observatory.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] He added, "Never before was such a corps of observers known." But, he pointed out to his fellow scientists, his critical need was for more "simultaneous observations".
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] "The work," Maury stated, "is not exclusively for the benefit of any nation or age".
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Coffin of Easton, Pennsylvania, and Professor Stephen Alexander of Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] This was scientific cooperation, and Maury went back to Washington with great hopes for the future.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In 1850, the first female members were accepted: astronomer Maria Mitchell and entomologist Margaretta Morris.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Science educator Almira Hart Lincoln Phelps was elected in 1859.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] By 1860, membership increased to over 2,000.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Although the AAAS became dormant during the American Civil War (their August 1861 meeting in Nashville, Tennessee, was postponed indefinitely after the outbreak of the first major engagement of the war at Bull Run), the association recovered after the end of the hostilities.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In 1866, Frederick Barnard presided over the first meeting of the resurrected AAAS at a meeting in New York City.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Following the revival of the AAAS, the group had considerable growth.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The AAAS permitted all people, regardless of scientific credentials, to join.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The AAAS did, however, institute a policy of granting the title of "Fellow of the AAAS" to well-respected scientists within the organization.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Also, the reputation of the AAAS was somewhat tarnished, because its 3rd president Alexander Dallas Bache used the Society as a lobbying tool for his agency, the US Coast Survey.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Several prominent scientists lost interest in the AAAS, and the society's influence declined.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The next turning point in the AAAS history was the partnership with journal *Science*, which became the society's official publication in 1900, and provided the AAAS with some revenue through subscription and advertising.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The AAAS become the sole owner of *Science* in 1946.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Another important event for the society was the establishment of its Congressional Fellowship program in 1973, which was kick-started by a US$10,000 donation from William T.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Leshner, AAAS CEO from 2001 until 2015, published many op-ed articles discussing how many people integrate science and religion in their lives.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] He has opposed the insertion of non-scientific content, such as creationism or intelligent design, into the scientific curriculum of schools.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In February 2007, the AAAS used satellite images to document human rights abuses in Burma.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The next year, AAAS launched the Center for Science Diplomacy to advance both science and the broader relationships among partner countries, by promoting science diplomacy and international scientific cooperation.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In 2012, AAAS published op-eds, held events on Capitol Hill and released analyses of the U.S. federal research-and-development budget, to warn that a budget sequestration would have severe consequences for scientific progress.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] AAAS covers various areas of sciences and engineering.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] It has 24 sections, each with a committee and its chair.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] These committees are also entrusted with the annual evaluation and selection of Fellows.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The most recent Constitution of the AAAS, enacted on January 1, 1973, establishes that the governance of the AAAS is accomplished through four entities: a President, a group of administrative officers, a Council, and a board of directors.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Individuals elected to the presidency of the AAAS hold a three-year term in a unique way.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The first year is spent as president-elect, the second as president and the third as chairperson of the board of directors.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In accordance with the convention followed by the AAAS, presidents are referenced by the year in which they left office.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Geraldine Richmond is the president of AAAS for 2015–16; Phillip Sharp is the board chair; and Barbara A.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Each took office on the last day of the 2015 AAAS Annual Meeting in February 2015.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] On the last day of the 2016 AAAS Annual Meeting, February 15, 2016, Richmond will become the chair, Schaal will become the president, and a new president-elect will take office.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Past presidents of AAAS have included some of the most important scientific figures of their time.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Among them: explorer and geologist John Wesley Powell (1888); astronomer and physicist Edward Charles Pickering (1912); anthropologist Margaret Mead (1975); and biologist Stephen Jay Gould (2000).
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] There are three classifications of high-level administrative officials that execute the basic, daily functions of the AAAS.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] These are the executive officer, the treasurer and then each of the AAAS's section secretaries.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The current CEO of AAAS and executive publisher of *Science* magazine is Sudip Parikh.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The current Editor in Chief of Science magazine is Holden Thorp.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The AAAS has 24 "sections" with each section being responsible for a particular concern of the AAAS.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] AAAS affiliates include 262 societies and academies of science, serving more than 10 million members, from the Acoustical Society of America to the Wildlife Society, as well as non-mainstream groups like the Parapsychological Association.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The council is composed of the members of the Board of Directors, the retiring section chairmen, elected delegates and affiliated foreign council members.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Among the elected delegates there are always at least two members from the National Academy of Sciences and one from each region of the country.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The President of the AAAS serves as the Chairperson of the council.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Members serve the council for a term of three years.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The council meets annually to discuss matters of importance to the AAAS.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] They have the power to review all activities of the Association, elect new fellows, adopt resolutions, propose amendments to the Association's constitution and bylaws, create new scientific sections, and organize and aid local chapters of the AAAS.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The Council recently has new additions to it from different sections which include many youngsters as well.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] John Kerry of Chicago is the youngest American in the council and Akhil Ennamsetty of India is the youngest foreign council member.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The board of directors is composed of a chairperson, the president, and the president-elect along with eight elected directors, the executive officer of the association and up to two additional directors appointed by elected officers.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Members serve a four-year term except for directors appointed by elected officers, who serve three-year terms.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The current chairman is Gerald Fink, Margaret and Herman Sokol Professor at Whitehead Institute, MIT.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Fink will serve in the post until the end of the 2016 AAAS Annual Meeting, 15 February 2016.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The board of directors has a variety of powers and responsibilities.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] It is charged with the administration of all association funds, publication of a budget, appointment of administrators, proposition of amendments, and determining the time and place of meetings of the national association.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The board may also speak publicly on behalf of the association.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The board must also regularly correspond with the council to discuss their actions.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The AAAS council elects every year, its members who are distinguished scientifically, to the grade of fellow (**FAAAS**).
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Election to AAAS is an honor bestowed by their peers and elected fellows are presented with a certificate and rosette pin.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Formal meetings of the AAAS are numbered consecutively, starting with the first meeting in 1848.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Meetings were not held 1861–1865 during the American Civil War, and also 1942–1943 during World War II.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Since 1946, one meeting has occurred annually, now customarily in February.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Each year, the AAAS gives out a number of honorary awards, most of which focus on science communication, journalism, and outreach – sometimes in partnership with other organizations.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The awards recognize "scientists, journalists, and public servants for significant contributions to science and to the public's understanding of science".
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The awards are presented each year at the association's annual meeting.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] These policy fellows spend one or two years working for the executive (130 positions), legislative (5 positions) or judicial (1 position) branches.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The society's flagship publication is *Science*, a weekly interdisciplinary scientific journal.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Other peer-reviewed journals published by the AAAS in the "*Science* family of journals" are *Science Signaling*, *Science Translational Medicine*, *Science Immunology*, *Science Robotics* and the interdisciplinary *Science Advances*.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] They also publish the non-peer-reviewed *Science & Diplomacy*.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The society previously published the review journal *Science Books & Films* (SB&F).
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] AAAS also publishes on behalf of other organizations through the Science Partner Journals (SPJ) program, with a focus on online-only open access journals.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] SciLine is a philanthropically funded and editorially independent service for journalists and scientists.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Its launch was announced in an October 27, 2017 article in Science by founding director Rick Weiss, former communications chief at the White House Office of Science and Technology Policy and science reporter at the Washington Post.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Its stated mission is to increase the amount and quality of research-backed evidence in news stories by connecting U.S. journalists to scientists and to validated scientific information.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Reporters in the United States can access SciLine's services, which include expert-matching, general media briefings, expert quote sheets, and quick fact sheets.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] As of July 2021, SciLine had fulfilled approximately 2,000 requests from 650 journalists through its expert-matching service.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] SciLine's financial supporters include the Quadrivium Foundation, the Chan Zuckerberg Initiative, the John S. and James L.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Knight Foundation, the Rita Allen Foundation, and the Heinz Endowments.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In 1996, AAAS launched the **EurekAlert!** website, an editorially independent nonprofit news release distribution service covering all areas of science, medicine and technology.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] EurekAlert! provides news in English, Spanish, French, German, Portuguese, Japanese, and, from 2007, in Chinese.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Working staff journalists and freelancers who meet eligibility guidelines can access the latest studies before publication and obtain embargoed information in compliance with the U.S.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Securities and Exchange Commission's Regulation Fair Disclosure policy.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] By early 2018, more than 14,000 reporters from more than 90 countries have registered for free access to embargoed materials.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] More than 5,000 active public information officers from 2,300 universities, academic journals, government agencies, and medical centers are credentialed to provide new releases to reporters and the public through the system.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In 1998, European science organizations countered Eurekalert! with a press release distribution service AlphaGalileo.
[src:aaron-cicourel/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] EurekAlert! has fallen under criticism for lack of press release standards and for generating churnalism.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The **Autonomous University of Madrid** (Spanish: *Universidad Autónoma de Madrid*; **UAM**), commonly known as **la Autónoma**, is a Spanish public university located in Madrid, Spain.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The university was founded in 1968 by royal decree.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] UAM is widely respected as one of the most prestigious universities in Europe.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] According to the QS World University Rankings 2022, UAM is ranked as the top university in Spain and has consistently ranked as #1 in Spain in the *El País* University rankings, published annually.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Among its notable alumni, which include every president that the Supreme Court of Spain and Constitutional Court of Spain has had, is the current King of Spain, Felipe VI, who studied the Licenciatura en Derecho (Law) and is the president of UAM’s alumni society.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The campus of the university spans a rural tract of 650 acres (260 ha), mostly around metropolitan Madrid.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Founded in 1968, its main campus, Cantoblanco, is located near the cities of Alcobendas, San Sebastián de los Reyes and Tres Cantos.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] UAM's Cantoblanco Campus holds most of the university's facilities.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Of these, nearly 770,000 m2 (8,300,000 sq ft) are urbanised and about a third of them are garden areas.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] UAM offers 94 doctorate programs across the university.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] According to a study carried out by the newspaper *El Mundo*, in 2021, UAM was the best university in the country to study biology, nursing, medicine, physics and law, within the 50 careers with the highest demand.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The Stabilization Plan of 1959 and the development plans of the 1960s boosted the Spanish economy after years of austerity and the self-sufficiency-based economy.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The end of diplomatic and economic isolation led to an economic boom in Spain that resulted in the consolidation of a middle class similar to that of other Western European nations.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The demand for higher education increased, and the Spanish university system grew increasingly congested.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The Autonomous University of Madrid was established by the 5-1968 Decree approved by the Spanish Council of Ministers during the Francoist dictatorship along with the Autonomous University of Barcelona and the University of Bilbao.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] This decree was sponsored by the then-Minister of Science and Education, José Luis Villar Palasí, in order to restructure the Spanish university system.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The name *Universidad Autónoma de Madrid* first appeared in an executive order by the Ministry which was published on 13 August 1968.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] On 8 June 2018 the Autonomous University of Madrid celebrated its 50th anniversary with a series of commemorative events.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] UAM's Cantoblanco Campus is home to most of the university's facilities.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] It is located 15 km north of Madrid and has an extension of over 2,200,000 m2.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Of these are nearly 770,000 are urbanised and about a third of them are garden areas.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The campus was designed as a university town that was to be self-sufficient, but also would be situated away from Madrid in order to keep student activity against the Francoist dictatorship away from the capital.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Initially, the campus held the faculties of philosophy and liberal arts, law, economics, business management, and science, as well as the rectorate, several other service buildings and sports facilities.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The university's other facilities, the faculty of medicine and the teacher training Santa Maria school are in downtown Madrid.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] There are two other teacher training schools in Segovia and in Cuenca.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The original faculties were housed in interconnected buildings with several patios in between them.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Characteristic to each building is a large number of stairs in its corridors, initially designed to prevent students from running in case of police raids.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Currently, this fact has been considered by many university officials as a setback in the integration of handicapped students.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The newest facilities were built in a contemporary style, being more accessible and allowing more free movement to students.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Sporting facilities include two swimming pools (an indoor one and an outdoor one), two multiple-use pavilions, and outdoor tennis, football, basketball, paddle tennis, rugby, and futsal and beach volleyball courts.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Other services on campus include 16 cafeterias and other eating facilities, medical services, a pharmacy with optic care, a foreign languages pavilion, and a bookstore.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The campus also houses several research facilities partnered with the Spanish Scientific Research Council (CSIC).
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Cantoblanco Campus is accessible by train belonging to Renfe Cercanias Commuter service (station Cantoblanco-Universidad), or by the Madrid Region Commuter Bus service.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The campus is located in the B1 area of the Madrid Transports Consortium.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] UAM's faculty of medicine is located north of Madrid near La Paz teaching hospital (that acts as one of the faculty's teaching hospitals, as Puerta de Hierro Majadahonda Hospital, La Princesa Hospital, Niño Jesús Hospital and Fundación Jiménez Díaz do).
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Juan Luis Vives Residence Hall was UAM's first residential facility.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] It is located in the Plaza Castilla area in northern Madrid.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] It has 130 residents and holds several cultural activities for the university.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] La Cristalera residence is located in Miraflores de la Sierra, a village north of Madrid that was acquired by the university in 1989.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] It is used for conferences and meetings and is the main centre of UAM's summer courses.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The UAM is divided into eight faculties and superior schools that support and coordinate most of the university's academic and administrative activity.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Each faculty is divided into departments that coordinate the teaching and research of the different subjects.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Researchers can organise into research institutes in order to coordinate their activities in a specific research field.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The university totals up to 59 departments and eight research institutes.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] In addition to these, the UAM has seven associate schools, which are not completely part of UAM's administrative structure, but issue UAM-recognised titles and are under UAM's academic regulations.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] UAM administration is established according to the 2023 Organic Law of the University System (LOSU).
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The Senior Academic and Administrative Officer of the Autonomous University of Madrid is the rector, who must be, by law, a chair professor serving in the university, elected every four years with a two-term limit by universal graded suffrage.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The current rector is Amaya Mendikoetxea, chair of English Linguistics, who was elected in 2021, becoming the second woman Rector of the University.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Per the university's social board, the rector also designates the manager as part of his team, which oversees the university's economic and administrative activity.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] UAM's collective government bodies are the University Assembly, The Board of Governors, and The Social Board.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The University Assembly is made up of 153 full professors, 84 students, 27 hired, associate, or emeritus professors, 27 members of the non-teaching personnel, 9 research or teaching trainees, the rector, the secretary-general, and the manager.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] It is the highest representative body of the university.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] It elaborates the university's general guidelines, changes or passes a new university charter, elects twenty members of the Board of Governors, and elects the university Ombudsman.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The Board of Governors is the ordinary governmental body of the university.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] It controls and passes regulations on most of the university's academic, personnel, and administrative issues.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The Social Board is the body responsible for the relations between the university and society.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Its members are designated by trade unions, the municipality of Madrid, employers unions, companies related to the university, the Madrid Assembly and the Board of Governors of the university.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] It also oversees the universities financial activities and passes the university budget.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Faculties are headed by a dean, whilst the responsible of the polytechnic school is called head.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] They are elected in the same way as the rector and have also a limit of two four-year terms.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] They are aided by vice deans or deputy heads.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] They are overseen by a faculty or school board.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Departments are led by the head of the department and overseen by the department council.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] UAM offers Spanish undergraduates fully recognized degrees.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] There are the *Diplomatura* and *Ingenierías Técnicas* (technical engineering), which are three-year studies equivalent to an associate degree.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] *Licenciaturas* and *Ingenierías Superiores* are four to five years studies equivalent to a bachelor's degree.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Along with that, UAM offers second level *licenciaturas*, which allow people who have a diplomatura to obtain a *licenciatura* by taking courses.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] In other case, they must have at least the first two or three years of a *licenciatura* and combined degree, which are very popular among Spanish students.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] They also offer courses in languages other than Spanish.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] UAM offers 94 PhD programs in all of the universities programs.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] It also offers 72 master's degrees, and with the implementation of the Bologna Process 16 recognised master's degrees for the academic year of 2006–07.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] In addition, the alliance of the four leading Spanish public Universities, two in Madrid (Autónoma University of Madrid and Universidad Carlos III) and two in Barcelona (Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona, Universitat Pompeu Fabra) allows close collaboration between projects and researchers.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The UAM was ranked first amongst Spanish universities by the El Mundo University Supplement (known as "Las 50 Carreras").
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] It has also consistently ranked as the #1 law school in Spain for the past 100 years.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] For the subject "Mathematics" the university was ranked within top 51-75 universities in the world (within top 12 in Europe).
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] It was the Spanish university with the most researchers among the most cited according to the Thomson Reuters ranking citation in 2011.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The Autonomous University of Madrid has an active student body, having organised one of Spain's most important events against the dictatorship in 1976 called the Iberian Peoples Festival.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] UAM has over a hundred student societies covering activities ranging from student unionism to theatre and music.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The oldest active association in UAM is the Law Students Association (AED in Spanish), a left-leaning student union established in 1981.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Furthermore, there are new prominent societies in the field of social sciences, such a Debate Society (Sociedad de Debates UAM) and a Model UN society (UAM-I-MUN), both founded and run mainly by law students.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] UAM does not have a formal student government body, as it has been rejected by students in several occasions, and instead students elect different student unions (usually with difference on political issues) to the different university government bodies.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] UAM is also a festive campus, holding several festivals during spring.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The most important one was the Spring festival held until 1993, but halted due to overcrowding.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Since then minor festivals have been held by student associations.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] These festivals usually consist of rock concerts by amateur rock bands (many of which have members that are UAM) from midday until dusk.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] According to university regulations, festival profits have to be destined to charities or to the organisation of cultural events.
[src:aaron-cicourel/autonomous-university-of-madrid] In 2005, due to overcrowding of the festivals that led to several problems, university officials suspended further festivals until a more convenient place for their celebration would be found.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley is home to the oldest campus in the University of California, the University of California, Berkeley, and the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, which is managed and operated by the university.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] It also has the Graduate Theological Union, one of the largest religious studies institutions in the world.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley is considered one of the most socially progressive cities in the United States.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The site of today's City of Berkeley was the territory of the Chochenyo/Huchiun Ohlone people when the first Europeans arrived.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Human remains and skeletons from Native American burials have been unearthed in West Berkeley and on campus alongside Strawberry Creek.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Other artifacts were discovered in the 1950s in the downtown area during remodeling of a commercial building, near the upper course of the creek.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The first people of European descent (most of whom were of mixed race and born in America) arrived with the De Anza Expedition in 1776.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The De Anza Expedition led to establishment of the Spanish Presidio of San Francisco at the entrance to San Francisco Bay (the "Golden Gate)." Luis Peralta was among the soldiers at the Presidio.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] For his services to the King of Spain, he was granted a vast stretch of land on the east shore of San Francisco Bay (the *contra costa*, "opposite shore") for a ranch, including that portion that now comprises the City of Berkeley.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Luis Peralta named his holding "Rancho San Antonio." The primary activity of the ranch was raising cattle for meat and hides, but hunting and farming were also pursued.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Eventually, Peralta gave portions of the ranch to each of his four sons.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] What is now Berkeley lies mostly in the portion that went to Peralta's son Domingo, with a little in the portion that went to another son, Vicente.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] No artifact survives of the Domingo or Vicente ranches, but their names survive in Berkeley street names (Vicente, Domingo, and Peralta).
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] However, legal title to all land in the City of Berkeley remains based on the original Peralta land grant.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The Peraltas' Rancho San Antonio continued after Alta California passed from Spanish to Mexican sovereignty following the Mexican War of Independence.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] However, the advent of U.S. sovereignty after the Mexican–American War, and especially, the gold rush, saw the Peraltas' lands quickly encroached on by squatters and diminished by dubious legal proceedings.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The lands of the brothers Domingo and Vicente were quickly reduced to reservations close to their respective ranch homes.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The rest of the land was surveyed and parceled out to various American claimants (*See* Kellersberger's Map).
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Politically, the area that became Berkeley was initially part of a vast Contra Costa County.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] On March 25, 1853, Alameda County was created from a partition of Contra Costa County, as well as from a small portion of Santa Clara County.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The area that became Berkeley was then the northern part of the "Oakland Township" subdivision of Alameda County.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] During this period, "Berkeley" was mostly a mix of open land, farms, and ranches, with a small, though busy, wharf by the bay.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In 1866, Oakland's private College of California looked for a new site.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] It settled on a location north of Oakland along the foot of the Contra Costa Range (later called the Berkeley Hills) on Strawberry Creek, at an elevation of about 500 feet (150 m) above the bay, commanding a view of the Bay Area and the Pacific Ocean through the Golden Gate.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] According to the *Centennial Record of the University of California*, "In 1866, at Founders' Rock, a group of College of California men watched two ships standing out to sea through the Golden Gate.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The College of California's College Homestead Association planned to raise funds for the new campus by selling off adjacent parcels of land.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] To this end, they laid out a plat and street grid that became the basis of Berkeley's modern street plan.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Their plans fell far short of their desires, and they began a collaboration with the State of California that culminated in 1868 with the creation of the public University of California.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] As construction began on the new site, more residences were constructed in the vicinity of the new campus.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] At the same time, a settlement of residences, saloons, and various industries grew around the wharf area called Ocean View.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] A horsecar ran from Temescal in Oakland to the university campus along what is now Telegraph Avenue.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] By the 1870s, the transcontinental railroad reached its terminus in Oakland.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In 1876, a branch line of the Central Pacific Railroad, the Berkeley Branch Railroad, was laid from a junction with the mainline called Shellmound (now a part of Emeryville) into what is now downtown Berkeley.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] That same year, the mainline of the transcontinental railroad into Oakland was re-routed, putting the right-of-way along the bay shore through Ocean View.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] There was a strong prohibition movement in Berkeley at this time.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In 1876, the state enacted the "mile limit law", which forbade sale or public consumption of alcohol within one mile (1.6 km) of the new University of California.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Then, in 1899, Berkeley residents voted to make their city an alcohol-free zone.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Scientists, scholars and religious leaders spoke vehemently of the dangers of alcohol.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] On April 1, 1878, the people of Ocean View and the area around the university campus, together with local farmers, were granted incorporation by the State of California as the Town of Berkeley.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The first elected trustees of the town were the slate of Denis Kearney's anti-Chinese Workingman's Party, who were particularly favored in the working-class area of the former Ocean View, now called West Berkeley.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] During the 1880s Berkeley had segregated housing and anti-Chinese laws.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The area near the university became known for a time as East Berkeley.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Due to the influence of the university, the modern age came quickly to Berkeley.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Electric lights and the telephone were in use by 1888.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Electric streetcars soon replaced the horsecar.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] A silent film of one of these early streetcars in Berkeley can be seen at the Library of Congress website.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley's slow growth ended abruptly with the Great San Francisco earthquake of 1906.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The town and other parts of the East Bay escaped serious damage, and thousands of refugees flowed across the Bay.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Among them were most of San Francisco's painters and sculptors, who between 1907 and 1911 created one of the largest art colonies west of Chicago.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Cannon described the founding of the Berkeley Art Association and the rivalries of competing studios and art clubs.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In 1908, a statewide referendum that proposed moving the California state capital to Berkeley was defeated by a margin of about 33,000 votes.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The city had named streets around the proposed capitol grounds for California counties.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] They bear those names today, a legacy of the failed referendum.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] On March 4, 1909, following public referendums, the citizens of Berkeley were granted a new charter by the State of California, and the Town of Berkeley became the City of Berkeley.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Rapid growth continued up to the crash of 1929.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The Great Depression hit Berkeley hard, but not as hard as many other places in the U.S., thanks in part to the university.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In 1916, Berkeley implemented single-family zoning as an effort to keep minorities out of white neighborhoods.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] This has been described as the first implementation of single-family zoning in the United States.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] By 2021, nearly half of Berkeley's residential neighborhoods were still exclusively zoned for single-family homes.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In 2025, Berkeley legalized small multi-family buildings in most of the city.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] On September 17, 1923, a major fire swept down the hills toward the university campus and the downtown section.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Around 640 structures burned before a late-afternoon sea breeze stopped its progress, allowing firefighters to put it out.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The next big growth occurred with the advent of World War II, when large numbers of people moved to the Bay Area to work in the many war industries, such as the immense Kaiser Shipyards in nearby Richmond.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] One who moved out, but played a big role in the outcome of the war, was U.C. professor and Berkeley resident J.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] During the war, an Army base, Camp Ashby, was temporarily sited in Berkeley.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The element berkelium was synthesized utilizing the 60-inch (1.5 m) cyclotron at UC Berkeley, and named in 1949, in recognition of the university, thus placing the city's name in the list of elements.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] During the 1940s, many African Americans migrated to Berkeley.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In 1950, the Census Bureau reported Berkeley's population as 11.7% black and 84.6% white.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The postwar years brought moderate growth to the city, as events on the U.C. campus began to build up to the recognizable activism of the sixties.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In the 1950s, McCarthyism induced the university to demand a loyalty oath from its professors, many of whom refused to sign the oath on the principle of freedom of thought.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] House committee (HUAC) came to San Francisco to investigate the influence of communists in the Bay Area.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Their presence was met by protesters, including many from the university.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Meanwhile, a number of U.C. students became active in the civil rights movement.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Finally, in 1964, the university provoked a massive student protest by banning distribution of political literature on campus.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] This protest became the Free Speech Movement.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] As the Vietnam War rapidly escalated in the ensuing years, so did student activism at the university, particularly that organized by the Vietnam Day Committee.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley is strongly identified with the rapid social changes, civic unrest, and political upheaval that characterized the mid-to-late 1960s.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In that period, Berkeley—especially Telegraph Avenue—became a focal point for the hippie movement, which spilled over the Bay from San Francisco.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Many hippies were apolitical drop-outs, rather than students, but in the heady atmosphere of Berkeley in 1967–1969 there was considerable overlap between the hippie movement and the radical left.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] An iconic event in the Berkeley Sixties scene was a conflict over a parcel of university property south of the contiguous campus site that came to be called "People's Park".
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The battle over the disposition of People's Park resulted in a month-long occupation of Berkeley by the National Guard on orders of then-Governor Ronald Reagan.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In the end, the park remained undeveloped, and remained so for decades.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] A spin-off, *People's Park Annex*, was established at the same time by activist citizens of Berkeley on a strip of land above the Bay Area Rapid Transit ("BART") underground construction along Hearst Avenue northwest of the U.C. campus.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The land had also been intended for development, but was turned over to the city by BART and is now Ohlone Park.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The era of large public protest in Berkeley waned considerably with the end of the Vietnam War in 1975.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] While the 1960s were the heyday of liberal activism in Berkeley, it remains one of the most overwhelmingly Democratic cities in the United States.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] After the 1960s, Berkeley banned most new housing construction, in particular apartments.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Increasing enrollment at the university led to replacement of older buildings by large apartment buildings, especially in older parts of the city near the university and downtown.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Increasing enrollment also led the university to wanting to redevelop certain places of Berkeley, especially Southside, but more specifically People's Park.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Preservationists passed the Neighborhood Protection Ordinance in 1973 by ballot measure and the Landmarks Preservation Ordinance in 1974 by the City Council.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Together, these ordinances brought most new construction to a halt.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Facing rising housing costs, residents voted to enact rent control and vacancy control in 1980.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] For cities such as Berkeley, where rent control was already in place, the law limited the use of rent control to units built before the local rent-control law was enacted, i.e.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] During the 1970s and 1980s, activists increased their power in local government.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] This era also saw major developments in Berkeley's environmental and food culture.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley's last Republican mayor, Wallace J.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Alice Waters opened Chez Panisse in 1971.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The first curbside recycling program in the U.S. was started by the Ecology Center in 1973.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] As the city leaned more and more Democratic, local politics became divided between "Progressives" and "Moderates".
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] 1984 saw the Progressives take the majority for the first time.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Nancy Skinner became the first UC Berkeley student elected to City Council.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In 1986, in reaction to the 1984 election, a ballot measure switched Berkeley from at-large to district-based elections for city council.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In 1983, Berkeley's Domestic Partner Task Force was established, which in 1984 made policy recommendation to the school board, which passed domestic partner legislation.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The legislation became a model for similar measures nationwide.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In 1995, California's Costa–Hawkins Act ended vacancy control, allowing rents to increase when a tenant moved out.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Despite a slow down in 2005–2007, median home prices and rents remain dramatically higher than the rest of the nation, fueled by spillover from the San Francisco housing shortage and population growth.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] South and West Berkeley underwent gentrification, with some historically Black neighborhoods such as the Adeline Corridor seeing a 50% decline in Black / African American population from 1990 to 2010.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In the 1990s, public television's Frontline documentary series featured race relations at Berkeley's only public high school, Berkeley High School.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] With an economy dominated by the University of California and a high-demand housing market, Berkeley was relatively unaffected by the Great Recession.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] State budget cuts caused the university to increase the number of out-of-state and international students, with international enrollment, mostly from Asia, rising from 2,785 in 2007 to 5,951 in 2016.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Since then, more international restaurants have opened downtown and on Telegraph Avenue, including East Asian chains such as Ippudo and Daiso.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] A wave of downtown apartment construction began in 1998.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In 2006, the Berkeley Oak Grove Protest began protesting construction of a new sports center annex to Memorial Stadium at the expense of a grove of oak trees on the UC campus.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The protest ended in September 2008 after a lengthy court process.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In 2007–2008, Berkeley received media attention due to demonstrations against a Marine Corps recruiting office in downtown Berkeley and a series of controversial motions by Berkeley's city council regarding opposition to Marine recruiting.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] During the fall of 2010, the Berkeley Student Food Collective opened after many protests on the UC Berkeley campus due to the proposed opening of the fast food chain Panda Express.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Students and community members worked together to open a collectively run grocery store right off of the UC Berkeley campus, where the community can buy local, seasonal, humane, and organic foods.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The Berkeley Student Food Collective still operates at 2440 Bancroft Way.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] On September 18, 2012, Berkeley became what may be the first city in the U.S. to officially proclaim a day recognizing bisexuals: September 23, which is known as Celebrate Bisexuality Day.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] On September 2, 2014, the city council approved a measure to provide free medical marijuana to low-income patients.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The Measure D soda tax was approved by Berkeley voters on November 4, 2014, the first such tax in the United States.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In the fall of 2011, the nationwide Occupy Wall Street movement came to two Berkeley locations: on the campus of the University of California and as an encampment in Civic Center Park.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] During a Black Lives Matter protest on December 6, 2014, police use of tear gas and batons to clear protesters from Telegraph Avenue led to a riot and five consecutive days and nights of protests, marches, and freeway occupations in Berkeley and Oakland.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Afterwards, changes were implemented by the Police Department to avoid escalation of violence and to protect bystanders during protests.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] During a protest against bigotry and U.S.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] President Donald Trump in August 2017, self-described anti-fascist protesters attacked Trump supporters in attendance.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Sometimes called "antifa", these ‘anti-fascist’ activists were clad in black shirts and other black attire, while some carried shields and others had masks or bandanas hiding their faces to help them evade capture after street fighting.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] These protests spanned February to September 2017 (See more at 2017 Berkeley Protests).
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In 2019, protesters took up residence in People's Park against tree-chopping and were arrested by police in riot gear.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Many activists saw this as the university preparing to develop the park.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The city of Berkeley has historically been a central location for homeless communities in the Bay Area.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The city has passed ordinances to oust homeless individuals from Berkeley on multiple occasions.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Despite efforts to improve social services and remove unhoused individuals from the streets, homelessness has continued to be a significant problem in Berkeley.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] A culture of anti-establishment and sociopolitical activism marked the 1960s.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The San Francisco Bay Area became a hotspot for hippie counterculture, and Berkeley became a haven for nonconformists and anarchists from all over the United States.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Most public discourse around homelessness in Berkeley at this time was centered around the idea of street-living as an expression of counterculture.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Many non-student youth and adolescents sought alternative lifestyles and opted for voluntary homelessness during this time.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In 1969, People's Park was created and eventually became a haven for "small-time drug dealers, street people, and the homeless".
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Although the City of Berkeley has moved unhoused individuals from its streets, sometimes even relocating them to an unused landfill, People's Park has remained a safe space for them since its inception.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The park has become one of the few relatively safe spaces for homeless individuals to congregate in Berkeley and the greater Bay Area.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Stereotypes of homeless people as deviant individuals who chose to live vagrant lifestyles continued to color the discourse around street-dwellers in American cities.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] However, this time period was also characterized by a subtle shift in the perception of unhoused individuals.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The public began to realize that homelessness affected not only single men, but also women, children, and entire families.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] This recognition set the stage for the City of Berkeley's attitude towards homelessness in the next decade.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Organizations such as Building Opportunities for Self Sufficiency (BOSS) were established in 1971 in response to the needs of individuals with mental illness being released to the streets by state hospital closures.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In the 1990s, the City of Berkeley faced a substantial increase in the need for emergency housing shelters and saw a rise in the average amount of time individuals spent without stable housing.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] As housing became a more widespread problem, the general public, Berkeley City Council, and the University of California became increasingly anti-homeless in their opinions.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In 1994, Berkeley City Council considered the implementation of a set of anti-homeless laws that the *San Francisco Chronicle* described as being "among the strictest in the country".
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] These laws prohibited sitting, sleeping and begging in public spaces, and outlawed panhandling from people in a variety of contexts, such as sitting on public benches, buying a newspaper from a rack, or waiting in line for a movie.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In February 1995, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) sued the city for infringing free speech rights through its proposed anti-panhandling law.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The following month, the Street Spirit, a monthly newspaper written for and by people experiencing homelessness, published its first of hundreds of issues covering homelessness in the Bay Area and across the nation.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In May of that same year, a federal judge ruled that the anti-panhandling law did violate the First Amendment, but left the anti-sitting and sleeping laws untouched.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Following the implementation of these anti-sitting and sleeping ordinances in 1998, Berkeley increased its policing of homeless adults and youth, particularly in the shopping district surrounding Telegraph Avenue.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The mayor at that time, Shirley Dean, proposed a plan to increase both social support services for homeless youth and enforcement of anti-encampment laws.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Unhoused youth countered this plan with a request for the establishment of the city's first youth shelter, more trash cans, and more frequent cleaning of public bathrooms.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The City of Berkeley's 2017 annual homeless report and point-in-time count (PIT) estimate that on a given night, 972 people are homeless.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Sixty-eight percent (664 people) of these individuals are also unsheltered, living in places not considered suitable for human habitation, such as cars or streets.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Long-term homelessness in Berkeley is double the national average, with 27% of the city's homeless population facing chronic homelessness.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Chronic homelessness has been on the rise since 2015, and has been largely a consequence of the constrained local housing market.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In 2015, rent in Alameda County increased by 25%, while the average household income only grew by 5%.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The City of Berkeley's 2017 report also estimated the number of unaccompanied youth in Berkeley at 189 individuals, 19% of the total homeless population in the city.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Homeless youth display greater risk of mental health issues, behavioral problems, and substance abuse, than any other homeless age group.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Furthermore, homeless youth identifying as LGBTQ+ are exposed to greater rates of physical and sexual abuse, and higher risk for sexually transmitted diseases, predominantly HIV.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The City of Berkeley has seen a consistent rise in the number of chronically homeless individuals over the past 30 years, and has implemented a number of different projects to reduce the number of people living on the streets.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In 2008, the City focused its efforts on addressing chronic homelessness.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] This led to a 48% decline in the number of chronically homeless individuals reported in the 2009 Berkeley PIT.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] However, the number of "hidden homeless" individuals (those coping with housing insecurity by staying at a friend or relative's residence), increased significantly, likely in response to rising housing costs and costs of living.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In 2012, the City considered measures that banned sitting in commercial areas throughout Berkeley.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The measure was met with strong public opposition and did not pass.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] However, the City saw a strong need for it to implement rules addressing encampments and public usage of space as well as assessing the resources needed to assist the unhoused population.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In response to these needs the City of Berkeley established the Homeless Task Force, headed by then-Councilmember Jesse Arreguín.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Since its formation, the Task Force has proposed a number of different recommendations, from expanding the City Homeless Outreach and Mobile Crisis Teams, to building a short-term transitional shelter for unhoused individuals.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] According to the United States Census Bureau, the city's 17.7-square-mile (46 km2) area includes 10.5 square miles (27 km2) of land and 7.2 square miles (19 km2) (40.83%) water, most of it part of San Francisco Bay.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley borders the cities of Albany, Oakland, and Emeryville and Contra Costa County, including unincorporated Kensington, as well as San Francisco Bay.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley lies within telephone area code 510 (until September 2, 1991, Berkeley was part of the 415 telephone code that now covers only San Francisco and Marin counties), and the postal ZIP codes are 94701 through 94710, 94712, and 94720 for the University of California campus.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Most of Berkeley lies on a rolling sedimentary plain that rises gently from sea level to the base of the Berkeley Hills.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] East of the Hayward Fault along the base of the hills, elevation increases more rapidly.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The highest peak along the ridge line above Berkeley is Grizzly Peak, at an elevation of 1,754 feet (535 m).
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] A number of small creeks run from the hills to the Bay through Berkeley: Codornices, Schoolhouse, and Strawberry Creeks are the principal streams.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Most of these are largely culverted once they reach the plain west of the hills.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The Berkeley Hills are part of the Pacific Coast Ranges, and run in a northwest–southeast alignment.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Exposed in the Berkeley Hills are cherts and shales of the Claremont Formation (equivalent to the Monterey Formation), conglomerate and sandstone of the Orinda Formation and lava flows of the Moraga Volcanics.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Of similar age to the Moraga Volcanics (extinct), within the Northbrae neighborhood of Berkeley, are outcroppings of erosion resistant rhyolite.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] These rhyolite formations can be seen in several city parks and in the yards of a number of private residences.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Indian Rock Park in the northeastern part of Berkeley near the Arlington/Marin Circle features a large example.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley is traversed by the Hayward Fault Zone, a major branch of the San Andreas Fault to the west.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] No large earthquake has occurred on the Hayward Fault near Berkeley in historic times (except possibly in 1836), but seismologists warn about the geologic record of large temblors several times in the deeper past.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The current assessment is that a Bay Area earthquake of magnitude 6.7 or greater within the next 30 years is likely, with the Hayward Fault having the highest likelihood among faults in the Bay Area of being the epicenter.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Moreover, like much of the Bay Area, Berkeley has many areas of some risk to soil liquefaction, with the flat areas closer to the shore at low to high susceptibility.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The 1868 Hayward earthquake did occur on the southern segment of the Hayward Fault in the vicinity of today's city of Hayward.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] This quake destroyed the county seat of Alameda County then located in San Leandro, and it subsequently moved to Oakland.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] It was strongly felt in San Francisco, causing major damage.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] It was regarded as the "Great San Francisco earthquake" prior to 1906.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] It produced a furrow in the ground along the fault line in Berkeley, across the grounds of the new State Asylum for the Deaf, Dumb and Blind then under construction, which was noted by one early University of California professor.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Although no significant damage was reported to most of the few Berkeley buildings of the time, the 1868 quake did destroy the vulnerable adobe home of Domingo Peralta in north Berkeley.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Today, evidence of the Hayward Fault's "creeping" is visible at various locations in Berkeley.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Cracked roadways, sharp jogs in streams, and springs mark the fault's path.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] However, since it cuts across the base of the hills, the creep is often concealed by or confused with slide activity.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Some of the slide activity itself, however, results from movement on the Hayward Fault.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] A notorious segment of the Hayward Fault runs lengthwise down the middle of Memorial Stadium at the mouth of Strawberry Canyon on the University of California campus.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Photos and measurements show the movement of the fault through the stadium.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley has a warm-summer Mediterranean climate (*Csb* in the Köppen climate classification), with warm, dry summers and cool, wet winters.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley's location directly opposite the Golden Gate ensures that typical eastward fog flow blankets the city more often than its neighbors.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The summers are cooler than a typical Mediterranean climate thanks to upwelling ocean currents along the California coast.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] These help produce cool and foggy nights and mornings.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Winter is punctuated with rainstorms of varying ferocity and duration, but also produces stretches of bright sunny days and clear cold nights.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] It does not normally snow, though occasionally the hilltops get a dusting.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Spring and fall are transitional and intermediate, with some rainfall and variable temperature.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Summer typically brings night and morning low clouds or fog, followed by sunny, warm days.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The warmest and driest months are typically June through September, with the highest temperatures occurring in September.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Mid-summer (July–August) is often a bit cooler due to the sea breezes and fog common then.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In a year, there are an average of 2.9 days with highs of 90 °F (32 °C) or higher, and an average of 0.8 days with lows of 32 °F (0 °C) or lower.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The highest recorded temperature was 107 °F (42 °C) on June 15, 2000, and July 16, 1993, and the lowest recorded temperature was 24 °F (−4 °C) on December 22, 1990.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] February is normally the wettest month, averaging 5.21 inches (132 mm) of precipitation.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Average annual precipitation is 25.40 inches (645 mm), falling on an average of 63.7 days each year.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The most rainfall in one month was 14.49 inches (368 mm) in February 1998.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The most rainfall in 24 hours was 6.98 inches (177 mm) on January 4, 1982.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] As in most of California, the heaviest rainfall years are usually associated with warm water El Niño episodes in the Pacific (e.g., 1982–83; 1997–98), which bring in drenching "Pineapple Express" storms.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In contrast, dry years are often associated with cold Pacific La Niña episodes.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Light snow has fallen on rare occasions.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Snow has generally fallen every several years on the higher peaks of the Berkeley Hills.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In the late spring and early fall, strong offshore winds of sinking air typically develop, bringing heat and dryness to the area.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In the spring, this is not usually a problem as vegetation is still moist from winter rains, but extreme dryness prevails by the fall, creating a danger of wildfires.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In September 1923, a major fire swept through the neighborhoods north of the university campus, stopping just short of downtown.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] On October 20, 1991, gusty, hot winds fanned a conflagration along the Berkeley–Oakland border, killing 25 people and injuring 150, as well as destroying 2,449 single-family dwellings and 437 apartment and condominium units.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Note: the US Census treats Hispanic/Latino as an ethnic category.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] This table excludes Latinos from the racial categories and assigns them to a separate category.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The 2020 United States census reported that Berkeley had a population of 124,321.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The population density was 11,874 people per square mile of land area (4,584/km2).
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] There were 17,018 (13.7%) of Hispanic or Latino ancestry, of any race.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] According to the 2022 American Community Survey estimate, the median income for a household was $104,716 and the median income for a family was $177,068.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Males had a median income of $102,565 versus $82,772 for females.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The per capita income for the city was $63,310.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] About 4.3% of families and 17.7% of the population were below the poverty line, including 6% of those under age 18 and 8.1% of those age 65 or over.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] There were 12,209 people (10.8%) of Hispanic or Latino ancestry, of any race.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] 6.8% of the city's population was of Mexican ancestry.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The Census reported that 99,731 people (88.6% of the population) lived in households, 12,430 (11.0%) lived in non-institutionalized group quarters, and 419 (0.4%) were institutionalized.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] There were 46,029 households, out of which 8,467 (18.4%) had children under the age of 18 living in them, 13,569 (29.5%) were opposite-sex married couples living together, 3,855 (8.4%) had a female householder with no husband present, 1,368 (3.0%) had a male householder with no wife present.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] There were 2,931 (6.4%) unmarried opposite-sex partnerships, and 961 (2.1%) same-sex married couples or partnerships.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] 16,904 households (36.7%) were made up of individuals, and 4,578 (9.9%) had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] There were 18,792 families (40.8% of all households); the average family size was 2.81.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The homeowner vacancy rate was 1.0%; the rental vacancy rate was 4.5%.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] 45,096 people (40.1% of the population) lived in owner-occupied housing units and 54,635 people (48.5%) lived in rental housing units.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] For every 100 females, there were 95.6 males.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 94.2 males.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] According to the 2011 American Community Survey 5-Year estimate, the median income for a household in the city was $60,908, and the median income for a family was $102,976.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Males had a median income of $67,476 versus $57,319 for females.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The per capita income for the city was $38,896.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] About 7.2% of families and 18.3% of the population were below the poverty line, including 13.2% of those under age 18 and 9.2% of those age 65 or over.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley has a higher-than-average crime rate, particularly property crime, though the crime rate has fallen significantly since 2000.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley is served by Amtrak (Capitol Corridor), AC Transit, BART (Ashby, Downtown Berkeley Station and North Berkeley) and bus shuttles operated by major employers including UC Berkeley and Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The Eastshore Freeway (Interstate 80 and Interstate 580) runs along the bay shoreline.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Each day there is an influx of thousands of cars into the city by commuting UC faculty, staff and students, making parking for more than a few hours an expensive proposition.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley has one of the highest rates of bicycle and pedestrian commuting in the nation.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley is the safest city of its size in California for pedestrians and cyclists, considering the number of injuries per pedestrian and cyclist, rather than per capita.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley has modified its original grid roadway structure through use of diverters and barriers, moving most traffic out of neighborhoods and onto arterial streets (visitors often find this confusing, because the diverters are not shown on all maps).
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley maintains a separate grid of arterial streets for bicycles, called Bicycle Boulevards, with bike lanes and lower amounts of car traffic than the major streets they often parallel.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Attempts to improve the biking infrastructure in Berkeley have been met with controversy.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In 2023, the Berkeley city council fired the city's top transportation official for a plan to remove dozens of parking spots on a street to build a protected bike lane.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley hosts car sharing network Zipcar.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Rather than owning (and parking) their own cars, members share a group of cars parked nearby.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Web- and telephone-based reservation systems keep track of hours and charges.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Several "pods" (points of departure where cars are kept) exist throughout the city, in several downtown locations, at the Ashby and North Berkeley BART stations, and at various other locations in Berkeley (and other cities in the region).
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Using alternative transportation is encouraged.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley has had recurring problems with parking meter vandalism.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In 1999, over 2,400 Berkeley meters were jammed, smashed, or sawed apart.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Starting in 2005 and continuing into 2006, Berkeley began to phase out mechanical meters in favor of more centralized electronic meters.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The Berkeley Branch line was extended from Shattuck and University to Vine Street ("Berryman's Station") in 1878.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Starting in 1882, Berkeley trains ran directly to the Oakland Pier.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In the 1880s, Southern Pacific assumed operations of the Berkeley Branch under a lease from its own paper affiliate, the Northern Railway.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] In 1911, Southern Pacific electrified this line and the several others it constructed in Berkeley, creating its East Bay Electric Lines division.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The huge and heavy cars specially built for these lines were called the "Red Trains" or the "Big Red Cars".
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The Shattuck line was extended and connected with two other Berkeley lines (the Ninth Street Line and the California Street line) at Solano and Colusa (the "Colusa Wye").
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] At this time, the Northbrae Tunnel and Rose Street Undercrossing were constructed, both of which still exist.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] (The Rose Street Undercrossing is not accessible to the public, being situated between what is now two backyards.) The fourth Berkeley line was the Ellsworth St. line to the university campus.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The first electric rail service in Berkeley was provided by several small streetcar companies starting in 1891.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Most of these were eventually bought up by the Key System of Francis "Borax" Smith who added lines and improved equipment.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The Key System's streetcars were operated by its East Bay Street Railways division.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Principal lines in Berkeley ran on Euclid, The Arlington, College, Telegraph, Shattuck, San Pablo, University, and Grove (today's Martin Luther King Jr.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The last streetcars ran in 1948, replaced by buses.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The first electric commuter interurban-type trains to San Francisco from Berkeley were put in operation by the Key System in 1903, several years before the Southern Pacific electrified its steam commuter lines.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Like the SP, Key trains ran to a pier serviced by the Key's own fleet of ferryboats, which also docked at the Ferry Building in San Francisco.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] After the Bay Bridge was built, the Key trains ran to the Transbay Terminal in San Francisco, sharing tracks on the lower deck of the Bay Bridge with the SP's red trains and the Sacramento Northern Railroad.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] It was at this time that the Key trains acquired their letter designations, which were later preserved by Key's public successor, AC Transit.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Today's F bus is the successor of the F train.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Before the Bridge, these lines were simply the Shattuck Avenue Line, the Claremont Line, the Westbrae Line, and the Sacramento Street Line, respectively.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] After the Southern Pacific abandoned transbay service in 1941, the Key System acquired the rights to use its tracks and catenary on Shattuck north of Dwight Way and through the Northbrae Tunnel to The Alameda for the F-train.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The SP tracks along Monterey Avenue as far as Colusa had been acquired by the Key System in 1933 for the H-train, but were abandoned in 1941.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] The Key System trains stopped running in April 1958.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] On December 15, 1962, the Northbrae Tunnel was opened to auto traffic.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley is the location of a number of nationally prominent businesses, many of which have been pioneers in their areas of operation.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Notable businesses include Chez Panisse, birthplace of California cuisine, Peet's Coffee's original store, the Claremont Resort, punk rock haven 924 Gilman, Saul Zaentz's Fantasy Studios, and Caffe Strada.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Notable former businesses include pioneer bookseller Cody's Books, The Nature Company, The North Face, Clif Bar energy foods, the Berkeley Co-op, and Caffe Mediterraneum.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley has relatively few chain stores for a city of its size, due to policies and zoning that promote small businesses and impose limits on the size of certain types of stores.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] Berkeley has a number of distinct neighborhoods.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] Surrounding the University of California campus are the most densely populated parts of the city.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] West of the campus is **Downtown Berkeley**, the city's traditional commercial core; home of the civic center, the city's only public high school, the busiest BART station in Berkeley, as well as a major transfer point for AC Transit buses.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] South of the campus is **Southside**, mainly a student ghetto, where much of the university's student housing is located.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] The busiest stretch of Telegraph Avenue is in this neighborhood.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] North of the campus is the quieter **Northside** neighborhood, the location of the Graduate Theological Union.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] Farther from the university campus, the influence of the university quickly becomes less visible.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] Most of Berkeley's neighborhoods are primarily made up of detached houses, often with separate in-law units in the rear, although larger apartment buildings are also common in many neighborhoods.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] Commercial activities are concentrated along the major avenues and at important intersections and frequently define the neighborhood within which they reside.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] In the southeastern corner of the city is the **Claremont District**, home to the Claremont Hotel.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] Also in the southeast is the **Elmwood District** known for its commercial area on College Avenue.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] West of Elmwood is **South Berkeley**, known for its weekend flea market at the Ashby Station.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] West of (and including) San Pablo Avenue, itself a major commercial and transport corridor, is **West Berkeley**, the historic commercial center of the city.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] This neighborhood and area includes the former unincorporated town of **Ocean View**.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] West Berkeley contains the remnants of Berkeley's industrial area, much of which has been replaced by retail and office uses, as well as residential live/work loft space, paralleling the decline of manufacturing in the United States.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] This area abuts the shoreline of the San Francisco Bay and is home to the Berkeley Marina.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] Also nearby is Berkeley's Aquatic Park, featuring an artificial linear lagoon of San Francisco Bay.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] North of downtown is **North Berkeley** which has its main commercial area nicknamed the "Gourmet Ghetto" because of the concentration of well-known restaurants and other food-related businesses.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] West of North Berkeley (roughly west of Sacramento and north of Cedar) is **Westbrae**, a small neighborhood centered on a small commercial area on Gilman Street and through which part of the Ohlone Greenway runs.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] Meanwhile, further north of North Berkeley are **Northbrae**, a master-planned subdivision from the early 20th century, and **Thousand Oaks**.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] Above these last three neighborhoods, on the western slopes of the Berkeley Hills are the neighborhoods of **Cragmont** and **La Loma Park**, notable for their dramatic views, winding streets, and numerous public stairways and paths.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] The city has many parks, and promotes greenery and the environment.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] Tilden Regional Park lies east of the city, occupying the upper extent of Wildcat Canyon between the Berkeley Hills and the San Pablo Ridge.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] The city is also heavily involved in creek restoration and wetlands restoration, including a planned *daylighting* of Strawberry Creek along Center Street.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] The Berkeley Marina and East Shore State Park flank its shoreline at San Francisco Bay and organizations like the Urban Creeks Council and Friends of the Five Creeks, the former of which is headquartered in Berkeley, support the riparian areas in the town and coastlines as well.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] César Chávez Park, near the Berkeley Marina, was built at the former site of the city dump.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] 165 buildings in Berkeley are designated as local landmarks or local structures of merit.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] Berkeley is home to the Chilean-American community's La Peña Cultural Center, the largest cultural center for this community in the United States.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] The Freight and Salvage is the oldest established full-time folk and traditional music venue west of the Mississippi River.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] Additionally, Berkeley is home to the off-Broadway theater Berkeley Repertory Theater, commonly known as "Berkeley Rep".
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] The Berkeley Repertory Theater consists of two stages, a school, and has received a Tony Award for Outstanding Regional Theatre.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] The historic Berkeley Art Museum and Pacific Film Archive (BAMPFA) is operated by UC Berkeley, and was moved to downtown Berkeley in January 2016.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] It offers many exhibitions and screenings of historic films, as well as outreach programs within the community.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] University of California, Berkeley's main campus is in the city limits.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] The Graduate Theological Union, a consortium of eight independent theological schools, is located a block north of the University of California Berkeley's main campus.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] The Graduate Theological Union has the largest number of students and faculty of any religious studies doctoral program in the United States.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] In addition to more theological schools, Zaytuna College, a newly established Muslim liberal-arts college, has taken 'Holy Hill' as its new home.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] The Institute of Buddhist Studies has been located in Berkeley since 1966.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] Wright Institute, a psychology graduate school, is located in Berkeley.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] Berkeley City College is a community college in the Peralta Community College District.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] The Berkeley Unified School District operates public schools.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] The first public school in Berkeley was the Ocean View School, now the site of the Berkeley Adult School located at Virginia Street and San Pablo Avenue.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] The public schools today are administered by the Berkeley Unified School District.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] In the 1960s, Berkeley was one of the earliest US cities to voluntarily desegregate, utilizing a system of buses, still in use.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] The district has eleven elementary schools and one public high school, Berkeley High School (BHS).
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] Established in 1880, BHS currently has over 3,000 students.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] The Berkeley High campus was designated a historic district by the National Register of Historic Places on January 7, 2008.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] Saint Mary's College High School, a Catholic school, also has its street address in Berkeley, although most of the grounds and buildings are actually in neighboring Albany.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] Berkeley has 11 public elementary schools and three middle schools.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] The East Bay campus of the German International School of Silicon Valley (GISSV) formerly occupied the Hillside Campus, Berkeley, California; it opened there in 2012.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] In December 2016, the GISSV closed the building, due to unmet seismic retrofit needs.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] Berkeley Public Library serves as the municipal library.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] University of California, Berkeley Libraries operates the University of California Berkeley libraries.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] Berkeley has a council–manager government.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] The mayor is elected at-large for a four-year term and is the ceremonial head of the city and the chair of the city council.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] The Berkeley City Council is composed of the mayor and eight council members elected by district who each serve four-year terms.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] Districts 2, 3, 5 and 6 hold their elections in years divisible by four while Districts 1, 4, 7 and 8 hold theirs in even-numbered years not divisible by four.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] The city council appoints a city manager, who is the chief executive of the city.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] Additionally, the city voters directly elect an independent city auditor, school board, and rent stabilization board.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] Most city officials, including council members, are elected using instant-runoff voting since November 2010.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] In 2014, the City of Berkeley passed a redistricting measure on the ballot to create the nation's first student supermajority district in District 7, which in 2018 elected Rigel Robinson, a 22-year-old UC Berkeley graduate and the youngest Councilmember in the city's history.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] While much of UC Berkeley's student housing is located in District 7, large dormitories also exist in Districts 6 and 8.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] The city's Public Health Division is one of four municipally operated public health agencies in California (the other three being Long Beach, Pasadena, and Vernon).
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] Though it is part of the city government, it qualifies for the same state funds as a county public health department.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] Berkeley is also part of Alameda County, for which the Government of Alameda County is defined and authorized under the California Constitution, California law, and the Charter of the County of Alameda.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] The county government provides countywide services, such as elections and voter registration, law enforcement, jails, vital records, property records, tax collection, and social services.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] The county's health department does not cover the city.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] Berkeley has been a Democratic stronghold in presidential elections since 1960, becoming one of the most Democratic cities in the country.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] The last Republican presidential candidate to receive at least one-quarter of the vote in Berkeley was Richard Nixon in 1968.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] Consistent with Berkeley's reputation as a strongly liberal and/or progressive city, in the 2016 presidential election more votes were won by Green Party presidential candidate Jill Stein than by Republican candidate Donald Trump.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] In the 2020 Presidential election, Joe Biden received 93.8% of the vote while Donald Trump received 4.0% of the vote.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] According to the California Secretary of State, as of October 20, 2025, Berkeley has 75,509 registered voters.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] Of those, 55,523 (73.53%) are registered Democrats, 2,317 (3.07%) are registered Republicans, 14,323 (18.97%) have declined to state a political party affiliation, and 3,346 (4.43%) are registered with a third party.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] Berkeley became the first city in the United States to pass a sanctuary resolution on November 8, 1971.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] The city had a daily newspaper, the *Berkeley Gazette*, which was founded c.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] The *Berkeley Barb* published counter-culture news from 1965 to 1980.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] Current media include *The Daily Californian*, the student newspaper of UC Berkeley; the *Berkeley Times*; and local online-only publications *Berkeleyside*, the *Berkeley Daily Planet*, and *The Berkeley Scanner*.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] Notable individuals who were born in and/or have lived in Berkeley include Kamala Harris, Steve Wozniak, scientists J.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] Robert Oppenheimer and Ernest Lawrence, actors Ben Affleck, and Andy Samberg, Major League Baseball broadcaster Matt Vasgersian, model Rebecca Romijn, Billie Joe Armstrong, lead singer of Green Day, Adam Duritz of Counting Crows, rapper Lil B, authors Ursula K.
[src:aaron-cicourel/berkeley-california-p02] Le Guin and Michael Chabon, entertainment and real estate mogul Herbie Herbert, and EDM producer KSHMR, and university presidents Blake R.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] In 2016 the British Deaf Association (BDA) said that, based on official statistics, it believes there are 151,000 people who use BSL in the UK, and 87,000 of these are deaf.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] This figure does not include professional BSL users, interpreters, translators, etc. unless they use BSL at home.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] By contrast, in the 2011 England and Wales Census 15,000 people living in England and Wales reported themselves using BSL as their main language.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] In Northern Ireland, there are about 4,500 users of BSL and 1,500 users of Irish Sign Language, an unrelated sign language.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] A hybrid version, dubbed "Northern Ireland Sign Language", is also used.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] On 18 March 2003 the UK government formally recognised BSL as a language in its own right.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] In 2022, the British Sign Language Act was passed, which legally recognised BSL as a language of England, Wales and Scotland.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] BSL is used in some educational establishments, but is not always the policy for deaf children in some local authority areas.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] As of January 2026, there is no GCSE qualification in British Sign Language available to students, but one is under development in England and planned for Wales.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] The Department for Education began to develop the GCSE in 2019, but the process was delayed due to the Covid-19 pandemic.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] In June 2023, the UK Government launched a consultation for the GCSE, with teaching initially planned to begin in schools from September 2025.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] In 2024, Qualifications Wales suspended development of its GCSE in BSL, setting a new goal to introduce it to schools in Wales in 2027.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] In 2025, Ofqual ran a second consultation to gather feedback on its proposed rules for the qualification in England, releasing the results and its final decisions on the rules in November.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] GCSE exam boards who want to run the qualification in England must next make detailed offers to Ofqual for accreditation based on these regulations.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Many British television channels broadcast programmes with in-vision signing, using BSL, as well as specially made programmes aimed mainly at deaf people such as the BBC's *See Hear* and Channel 4's *VEE-TV*.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] There is also a specially dedicated British Sign Language channel, LumoTV (previously BSL Zone), established in 2008.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] All BBC channels (excluding BBC One and BBC Alba) provide in-vision signing for some of their programmes.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] BBC Two also broadcasts in-vision signed repeats of the main channel's primetime programmes between 00:00 and 05:00 each weekday and early Saturday mornings.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] It also provides signing on weekday mornings between 08:00 and 09:00.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] In 2024, over 10% of Channel 4's programming was signed, including popular shows such as Hollyoaks and Gogglebox.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Published in 1992, the British Sign Language Dictionary was compiled for the British Deaf Association by the Deaf Studies Research Unit at the University of Durham.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] The dictionary was edited by David Brien, assisted by a team composed by Mary Brennan, Clark Denmark, Frances Elton, Liz Scott Gibson, Graham Turner and Dorothy Miles, among others.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] It depicts over 1,800 signs through pictures and diagrams, each sign accompanied by definitions, explanations and usage.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] The signs are ordered not alphabetically, as a dictionary of the English language, but rather according to the phonological characteristics of the language.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] For example, signs that are based on the "fist" handshape come before signs based on the "open hand" handshape.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] The foreword was written by Diana, Princess of Wales, who was the patron of the BDA.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] The British Sign Language Corpus Project, based at the Deafness Cognition and Language Research Centre (University College London), was funded between 2008 and 2011 to provide a video corpus of BSL in four regions (Bristol, Birmingham, London and Manchester).
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] It was succeeded by the BSL SignBank, which moved the BSL Corpus online between 2011 and 2015.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] It also draws on the 1992 BSL Dictionary for its vocabulary.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Certain signs used in Scotland, for example, may not be understood immediately, or not understood at all, by those in Southern England, or vice versa.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Some signs are even more local, occurring only in certain towns or cities (such as the Manchester system of number signs).
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Likewise, some may go in or out of fashion, or evolve over time, just as terms in oral languages do.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Families may have signs unique to them to accommodate for certain situations or to describe an object that may otherwise require fingerspelling.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Although the United Kingdom and the United States share English as the predominant spoken language, British Sign Language is quite distinct from American Sign Language (ASL), having only 31% signs identical, or 44% cognate.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] BSL is also distinct from Irish Sign Language (ISL), which is more closely related to French Sign Language (LSF) and ASL.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] BSL is also distinct from Signed English, a manually coded method expressed to represent the English language.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] The sign languages used in Australia and New Zealand, Auslan and New Zealand Sign Language respectively, evolved largely from 19th century BSL, and all retain the same manual alphabet and grammar and possess similar lexicons.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] The sign language used in Sri Lanka is also closely related to BSL despite the oral language not being English, demonstrating variation in distance between sign languages and spoken ones.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] While private correspondence from William Stokoe hinted at a formal name for the language in 1960, the first usage of the term "British Sign Language" in an academic publication was likely by Aaron Cicourel.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] The earliest known document describing the use of signing in a legal context is dated to c.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] 1324 and mentions John de Orleton, a deaf man assigning his property to a family member.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Published in 1450, the *History of the Syon Monastery at Lisbon and Brentford*, contains descriptions of signs—some of which are still in use.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] The earliest evidence of signing in registry records is from a marriage ceremony between a deaf man, Thomas Tilsye and Ursula Russel on 6 February 1576 at St Martin's Church, now Leicester Cathedral.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Richard Carew's *Survey of Cornwall* (1602) includes a description of Edward Bone, a deaf servant, meeting his deaf friend John Kempe.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Bone had some knowledge of Cornish and was able to lipread, but appeared to prefer signing.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] In particular, *Chirologia* focuses on the meanings of gestures, expressions and body language, and describes signs and gestures in use at the time, some of which resemble signs still in use, while *Philocopus* explores the use of lipreading by deaf people and the possibility of deaf education.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Another writer of the same time, George Dalgarno, recognised that sign language was unrelated to English.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] British Sign Language has evolved, as all languages do, from these origins by modification, invention and importation.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Thomas Braidwood, a teacher from Edinburgh, founded 'Braidwood's Academy for the Deaf and Dumb' in 1760, which is believed to be the first school for deaf children in Britain.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] The school primarily taught oral communication, however there is evidence of 'deaf signing' being used as a teaching method (albeit probably following the structure of English).
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] This *combined system* came to be known as the English method—a sort of midway point between French manualist and German oralist systems, and was the first codification of what would later develop into British Sign Language.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Joseph Watson was trained as a teacher of the deaf under Thomas Braidwood.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] He eventually left in 1792 to become the headmaster of the Asylum for the Deaf and Dumb in Bermondsey where he advocated for 'natural signing'—likely referring to the way deaf children naturally sign, as opposed to following English structure.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] This 'natural signing' is thought to be the precursor to modern BSL.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] In 1815 when Thomas Gallaudet visited England, the Braidwood school refused to teach him their methods unless he paid them.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] So instead, Gallaudet found himself in Paris, having been invited there by the much more accommodating Abbé Sicard.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Gallaudet would eventually take much of the what had learnt in France, back to the United States.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] As a consequence American Sign Language (ASL) today has a 60% similarity to modern French Sign Language and is almost unintelligible to users of British Sign Language.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] By the mid 1800s, sign was the most prominent mode of communication within deaf schools in Britain, and by 1870, there were 22 (often residential) schools found in most major cities around the country.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] The Second International Congress on Education of the Deaf, also known as the Milan Conference, was held in 1880, and proscribed the use of sign language in education; for the best part of a century, sign language was no longer used in the education of deaf children.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Signing was actively discouraged in schools by punishment, and deaf education emphasised teaching deaf children to learn to lip read and finger spell, due to the prevailing belief across Europe established that signing was bad.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Since there was no (or very little) exchange of sign language within educational establishments, signing was preserved through deaf clubs or within families.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Until the 1940s, sign language skills were passed between deaf people without a unified sign language system and many deaf people lived in residential institutions.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] In 1978, the government-issued Warnock Report advocated for the mainstreaming of deaf children which led to the closure of many deaf schools.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] During this time, the Total Communication method was popularised.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] From the 1970s there has been an increasing tolerance for the language, in part due to its recognition as a natural language by linguists.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] In the 1980s, BSL started to be used as language of instruction in schools again, alongside English.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] This decade saw the start of deaf programming on British television.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Deaf scholar and activist Paddy Ladd is credited with getting sign language on television and enabling deaf children to be educated in sign.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] BSL users campaigned to have BSL recognised on an official level.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Police and Criminal Evidence Act 1984 mandates the provision of interpreters.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] In 1999, the Federation of Deaf People (FDP) led a 4000-strong march in London to demand the recognition of BSL as a language.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] This can be considered to mark the first political march by the modern 'British Deaf Community', as an established community.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Let Sign Shine is a campaign started by Norfolk teenager Jade Chapman, whose sister is deaf, to raise awareness of BSL and to petition for BSL to be taught in schools.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] The campaign's petition to Parliament attracted support from over four thousand people.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Chapman won awards for her work including the education award category at the Bernard Matthews Youth Award 2014 for her work in raising awareness of the importance of sign language.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Having been donated £1,000 from the Bernard Matthews Youth Award, Let Sign Shine used this to start a British Sign Language course at Dereham Neatherd High School.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] In 2021, MP Rosie Cooper (a CODA) introduced the British Sign Language Bill to recognise BSL, this time as an official language (not merely its existence as had been done in 2003), which was backed by the government.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] After being dormant from June 2021, the bill began moving through Parliament on 28 January 2022, but during a meeting with stakeholders on 7 February, the language of the bill was revealed to have been pared down substantially, disappointing said stakeholders.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] The British Deaf Association stated that it was 'unhappy' with this removal of language from the bill.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] The British Sign Language Act received royal assent on 28th April 2022.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Linguistics is the study of language, including those like BSL that are not carried by sound.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] In all sign languages the great majority of 'words' (hand gestures) cannot be understood in other sign languages.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] How one language signs a certain number would be different from how another language signs it.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] The way sentences are constructed (syntax) differs from sign language to sign language, just as with different spoken languages.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] British Sign Language is described as a 'spatial language' as it "moves signs in space".
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Like many other sign languages, BSL phonology is defined by elements such as handshape, orientation, location, movement, and non-manual features.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] There are phonological components to sign language that have no meaning alone but work together to create a meaning of a signed word: hand shape, movement, location, orientation and facial expression.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] The meanings of words differ if one of these components is changed.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Signs can be identical in certain components but different in others, giving each a different meaning.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Facial expression falls under the nonmanual feature component of phonology.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] In common with other languages, whether spoken or signed, BSL has its own grammar which govern how phrases are signed.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] One important component of BSL is its use of proforms.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] A proform is "...any form that stands in the place of, or does the job of, some other form." Sentences are composed of two parts, in order: the subject and the predicate.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] The subject is the topic of the sentence, while the predicate is the commentary about the subject.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Question words are generally at the end of a sentence.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Topic-comment means that the topic of the signed conversation is first established, followed by an elaboration of the topic, being the 'comment' component.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] The canonical word order outside of the topic–comment structure is object–subject–verb (OSV), and noun phrases are head-initial.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] The language continues to evolve as older signs such as *alms* and *pawnbroker* have fallen out of use and new signs such as *internet* and *laser* have been coined.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] The evolution of the language and its changing level of acceptance meant that older users tend to use more finger spelling while younger ones make use of a wider range of signs.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] In 2019, over 100 signs for scientific terms, including 'deoxyribonucleotide' and 'deoxyribonucleoside', were added to BSL, after being conceived by Liam Mcmulkin, a deaf graduate of the University of Dundee, who had found finger-spelling such words tiresome, during his degree course.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Similarly, architects Chris Laing and Adolfs Kristapsons developed a project called SignStrokes which developed new signs for the built environment, having not wanted to continuously make new signs for different architectural concepts.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] British Sign Language can be learnt from formal institutions throughout the UK and three examination systems exist.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Courses are provided by community colleges, local centres for deaf people and private organisations.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] A teaching qualification programme was started by the British Deaf Association in 1984 at the University of Durham, called BSL Tutor Training Course, which closed in 1999.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] National awarding organisations run training for BSL teachers.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Each of these organisations has its own curriculum, teaching materials and resources.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] There are two qualification routes: via post-graduate studies, or via National Vocational Qualifications.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Deaf studies undergraduate courses with specific streams for sign language interpreting exist at several British universities; post-graduate level interpreting diplomas are also on offer from universities and one private company.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Course entry requirements vary from no previous knowledge of BSL to NVQ level 6 BSL (or equivalent).
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] The qualification process allows interpreters to register with the National Registers of Communication Professionals with Deaf and Deafblind People (NRCPD), a voluntary regulator.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Registrants are asked to self-certify that they have both cleared a DBS (Disclosure and Barring Service) check and are covered by professional indemnity insurance.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Completing a level 3 BSL language assessment and enrolling on an approved interpreting course allows applications to register as a TSLI (Trainee Sign Language Interpreter).
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] After completing an approved interpreting course, trainees can then apply to achieve RSLI (Registered Sign Language Interpreter) status.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] RSLIs are currently required by NRCPD to log Continuous Professional Development activities.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Post-qualification, specialist training is still considered necessary to work in specific critical domains.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] Communication support workers (CSWs) are professionals who support the communication of deaf students in education at all ages, and deaf people in many areas of work, using British Sign Language and other communication methods such as Sign Supported English.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] The qualifications and experience of CSWs vary: some are fully qualified interpreters, others are not.
[src:aaron-cicourel/british-sign-language] There are currently two well-established BSL language learning apps and web platforms: Bright BSL and Lingvano.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The university was renamed Columbia College in 1784 following the American Revolution, and in 1787 was placed under a private board of trustees headed by former students Alexander Hamilton and John Jay.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In 1896, the campus was moved to its current location and renamed Columbia University.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Columbia is organized into 17 schools, two affiliated colleges—Barnard College and Teachers College—and two affiliated seminaries—Jewish Theological Seminary (JTS) and Union Theological Seminary (UTS).
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The university's research efforts include the Lamont–Doherty Earth Observatory, the Goddard Institute for Space Studies, and accelerator laboratories with Big Tech firms such as Amazon and IBM.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Columbia is a founding member of the Association of American Universities and was the first school in the United States to grant the MD degree.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The university also administers and annually awards the Pulitzer Prize.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Discussions regarding the founding of a college in the Province of New York began as early as 1704.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Classes were initially held in July 1754 and were presided over by the college's first president, Samuel Johnson.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The college was officially founded on October 31, 1754, as King's College by royal charter of George II, making it the oldest institution of higher learning in the State of New York and the fifth oldest in the United States.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In 1763, Johnson was succeeded in the presidency by Myles Cooper, a graduate of The Queen's College, Oxford, and an ardent Tory.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In the charged political climate of the American Revolution, his chief opponent in discussions at the college was an undergraduate of the class of 1777, Alexander Hamilton.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The Irish anatomist, Samuel Clossy, was appointed professor of natural philosophy in October 1765 and later the college's first professor of anatomy in 1767.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Following the start of the American Revolutionary War and the arrival of Continental Army in 1776, the school suspended instruction for eight years.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The suspension continued through the military occupation of New York City by British troops until their departure in 1783.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] During this time, the college's library was looted and its sole building requisitioned for use as a military hospital first by American and then British forces.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The legislature agreed to assist the college.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] On May 1, 1784, it passed "an Act for granting certain privileges to the College heretofore called King's College".
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The Act created a board of regents to oversee the resuscitation of King's College.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In April of that same year, a new charter was adopted for the college granted the power to a separate board of 24 trustees.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] For a period in the 1790s, with New York City as the federal and state capital and the country under successive Federalist governments, a revived Columbia operated under Federalists such as Hamilton and Jay.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] President George Washington and Vice President John Adams, in addition to both houses of Congress attended the college's commencement on May 6, 1789, as a tribute of honor to the alumni of the school who had been involved in the American Revolution.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In 1813, the college incorporated its medical school with The College of Physicians and Surgeons, a new school created by the Regents of New York, forming Columbia University College of Physicians and Surgeons.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In 1857, the college moved from the King's College campus at Park Place to a primarily Gothic Revival campus on 49th Street and Madison Avenue, where it remained for the next forty years.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] During the last half of the 19th century, under the presidency of Frederick A.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Barnard, for whom Barnard College is named, the institution rapidly assumed the shape of a modern university.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Barnard College was created in 1889 as a response to the university's refusal to accept women.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In 1896, university president Seth Low moved the campus from 49th Street to its present location, a more spacious campus in the developing neighborhood of Morningside Heights.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In March 1917, as a result of America's entrance into World War 1, Columbia president Nicholas Murray Butler formed the Columbia Reserve Officers Training Corps.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] All students over the age of 18 who passed a physical exam were entered into this program.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Within 4 months, over 1,400 students were enrolled within the program.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] They were one of 12 universities designated by the War department to create a naval section for the Student Army Training Corps.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] As part of this new program, the US Army charged Columbia to create a "War Issues" course.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In 1919, a similar course was created for Columbia students, a "peace issues" course that evolved into "Introduction to Contemporary Civilization in the West", part of the university's core curriculum for undergraduate students.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In 1919, Columbia established a student application process characterized by *The New York Times* as "the first modern college application".
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In 1928, Seth Low Junior College was established by Columbia University in order to mitigate the number of Jewish applicants to Columbia College.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The college was closed in 1936 due to the adverse effects of the Great Depression and its students were subsequently taught at the Morningside Heights campus, although they did not belong to any college but to the university at large.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In the 1940s, faculty members, including John R.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Dunning, Isidor Isaac Rabi, Enrico Fermi, and Polykarp Kusch, began what became the Manhattan Project, creating the first nuclear fission reactor in the Americas and researching gaseous diffusion.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In the aftermath of World War II, the discipline of international relations became a major scholarly focus of the university, and in response, the School of International and Public Affairs was founded in 1946, drawing upon the resources of the faculties of political science, economics, and history.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In 1947, University Extension, an evening school program open to all for a fee, was reorganized as an undergraduate college and designated the School of General Studies in response to the return of GIs after World War II.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The Columbia University Bicentennial was celebrated in 1954.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] During the 1960s, student activism reached a climax with protests in the spring of 1968, when hundreds of students occupied buildings on campus.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The incident forced the resignation of Columbia's president, Grayson Kirk, and the establishment of the University Senate.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Though several schools in the university had admitted women for years, Columbia College first admitted women in the fall of 1983, after a decade of failed negotiations with Barnard College, the all-female institution affiliated with the university, to merge the two schools.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Barnard College still remains affiliated with Columbia, and all Barnard graduates are issued diplomas signed by the presidents of Columbia University and Barnard College.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] During the late 20th century, the university underwent significant academic, structural, and administrative changes as it developed into a major research university.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] For much of the 19th century, the university consisted of decentralized and separate faculties specializing in Political Science, Philosophy, and Pure Science.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In 1979, these faculties were merged into the Graduate School of Arts and Sciences.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In 1995, the Division of Special Programs, later called the School of Continuing Education and now the School of Professional Studies, was established to reprise the former role of University Extension.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Bollinger became Columbia's 19th president in June 2002, succeeding George Rupp.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Bollinger was appointed in October 2001 after arriving from the presidency of the University of Michigan.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] His presidency emphasized campus expansion, defense of affirmative action in college admissions, support for government funding of private sector media, and opposition to disinformation.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Under Bollinger's tenure, the university publicly launched a record $4 billion capital campaign in September 2006.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Financial aid was improved, eliminating loans for undergraduates from families earning under $50,000, and additional funds were allocated to support Bollinger's efforts toward the Manhattanville campus expansion, which nearly doubled Columbia's physical footprint.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] This expansion was supported by a major gift from trustee Gerry Lenfest.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Globalization efforts continued with the World Leaders Forum and the creation of the Committee on Global Thought, chaired by Joseph Stiglitz.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The 2008 financial crisis impacted Columbia's endowment.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The endowment recovered, hitting $8.2B in Oct 2013.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Despite the downturn, the university pressed on with Manhattanville construction, receiving final state approval in June 2009.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In May 2011, following the repeal of "Don't Ask, Don't Tell," the University Senate voted 51–17 to invite ROTC back after a 40-year absence, and Bollinger announced an agreement with the Navy.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Columbia has maintained its Global Centers network (Amman, Athens, Beijing, Mumbai, Paris, Nairobi, Istanbul, Santiago, Rio de Janeiro, Tunis, Tel Aviv), aiming to increase global engagement and international student enrollment.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] From 2014 to 2021, Columbia University pursued significant physical expansion, notably opening major facilities on the Manhattanville campus (ZMBBI, Lenfest Center, The Forum).
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Key strategic initiatives launched included the Knight First Amendment Institute, Columbia World Projects, and the new Columbia Climate School (2020).
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] A $5 billion university capital campaign was launched (with a $1.5B A&S target), major gifts like $50M for A&S's Uris Hall renovation were secured, and the endowment grew significantly ($14.35B by mid-2021).
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In February 2022, Columbia's mathematics professor Michael Thaddeus published a website and argued that data submitted by Columbia for U.S.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] News college rankings was "inaccurate, dubious or highly misleading".
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] News & World Report* unranked Columbia citing failed verification.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In September 2022, Columbia acknowledged the submission of incorrect data to U.S.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In June 2023, Columbia announced its non-participation in the rankings.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In July 2025, Columbia offered to pay US$9 million to settle a class-action lawsuit by its students in Manhattan federal court over the alleged submission of false data to boost its U.S.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In January 2023, Columbia University announced that Minouche Shafik would be the school's 20th president.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Previously, Shafik served as president of the London School of Economics and Political Science.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The federal government also launched an investigation into antisemitism and then withdrew funding, prompting the university to adopt new policies and adjust disciplinary processes.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Claire Shipman was appointed acting president in March 2025.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Columbia also closed its Morningside Heights campus to the general public, allowing access only to holders of Columbia ID cards and approved guests.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In July 2025, Columbia finalized a $220 million settlement to resume federal funding, agreeing to implement a set of reforms to address anti-semitism.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The university also adopted the IHRA definition of antisemitism.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In January 2026, the university announced that it had chosen Jennifer Mnookin, the chancellor of the University of Wisconsin-Madison, as the next president of Columbia, effective July 1, 2026.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In March 2026, a $481 million ruling that Columbia University had won against software company Gen Digital for infringing patents related to cybersecurity technology was overturned.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit stated that Columbia's patents may be invalid and sent the case back to Virginia federal court.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The majority of Columbia's graduate and undergraduate studies are conducted in the Upper Manhattan neighborhood of Morningside Heights on Seth Low's late-19th century vision of a university campus where all disciplines could be taught at one location.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The campus was designed along Beaux-Arts planning principles by the architects McKim, Mead & White.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Columbia's main campus occupies more than six city blocks, or 32 acres (13 ha), in Morningside Heights, New York City, a neighborhood that contains a number of academic institutions.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The university owns over 7,800 apartments in Morningside Heights, housing faculty, graduate students, and staff.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Almost two dozen undergraduate dormitories (purpose-built or converted) are located on campus or in Morningside Heights.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Columbia University has an extensive tunnel system, more than a century old, with the oldest portions predating the present campus.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Some of these remain accessible to the public, while others have been cordoned off.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Butler Library is the largest in the Columbia University Libraries system and one of the largest buildings on the campus.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] It was completed in 1934 and renamed to Butler Library in 1946.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] As of 2020, Columbia's library system includes over 15.0 million volumes, making it the eighth largest library system and fifth largest collegiate library system in the United States.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Several buildings on the Morningside Heights campus are listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Low Memorial Library, a National Historic Landmark and the centerpiece of the campus, is listed for its architectural significance.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Philosophy Hall is listed as the site of the invention of FM radio.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Also listed is Pupin Hall, another National Historic Landmark, which houses the physics and astronomy departments.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Here the first experiments on the fission of uranium were conducted by Enrico Fermi.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The uranium atom was split there ten days after the world's first atom-splitting in Copenhagen, Denmark.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Other buildings listed include Casa Italiana, the Delta Psi, Alpha Chapter building of St.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Anthony Hall, Earl Hall, and the buildings of the affiliated Union Theological Seminary.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] A statue by sculptor Daniel Chester French called *Alma Mater* is centered on the front steps of Low Memorial Library.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The statue represents a personification of the traditional image of the university as an *alma mater*, or "nourishing mother", draped in an academic gown and seated on a throne.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] She wears a laurel wreath on her head and holds in her right hand a scepter capped by a King's Crown, a traditional symbol of the university.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] A book, representing learning, rests on her lap.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The arms of her throne end in lamps, representing "Sapientia et Doctrina", or "Wisdom and Learning"; on the back of the throne is embossed an image of the seal of the university.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] "The Steps", alternatively known as "Low Steps" or the "Urban Beach", are a popular meeting area for Columbia students.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The term refers to the long series of granite steps leading from the lower part of campus (South Field) to its upper terrace.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In April 2007, the university purchased more than two-thirds of a 17 acres (6.9 ha) site for a new campus in Manhattanville, an industrial neighborhood to the north of the Morningside Heights campus.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Stretching from 125th Street to 133rd Street, Columbia Manhattanville houses buildings for Columbia's Business School, School of International and Public Affairs, Columbia School of the Arts, and the Jerome L.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Greene Center for Mind, Brain, and Behavior, where research will occur on neurodegenerative diseases such as Parkinson's and Alzheimer's.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The $7 billion expansion plan included demolishing all buildings, except three that are historically significant (the Studebaker Building, Prentis Hall, and the Nash Building), eliminating the existing light industry and storage warehouses, and relocating tenants in 132 apartments.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Replacing these buildings created 6.8 million square feet (630,000 m2) of space for the university.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Community activist groups in West Harlem fought the expansion for reasons ranging from property protection and fair exchange for land, to residents' rights.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Subsequent public hearings drew neighborhood opposition.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] As of December 2008, the State of New York's Empire State Development Corporation approved use of eminent domain, which, through declaration of Manhattanville's "blighted" status, gives governmental bodies the right to appropriate private property for public use.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] On May 20, 2009, the New York State Public Authorities Control Board approved the Manhanttanville expansion plan.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] NewYork-Presbyterian Hospital is affiliated with the medical schools of both Columbia University and Cornell University.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] News & World Report*'s "2020–21 Best Hospitals Honor Roll and Medical Specialties Rankings", it is ranked fourth overall and second among university hospitals.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Columbia's medical school has a strategic partnership with New York State Psychiatric Institute, and is affiliated with 19 other hospitals in the U.S. and four hospitals in other countries.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Health-related schools are located at the Columbia University Medical Center, a 20-acre (8.1 ha) campus located in the neighborhood of Washington Heights, fifty blocks uptown.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Other teaching hospitals affiliated with Columbia through the NewYork-Presbyterian network include the Payne Whitney Clinic in Manhattan, and the Payne Whitney Westchester, a psychiatric institute located in White Plains, New York.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] On the northern tip of Manhattan island (in the neighborhood of Inwood), Columbia owns the 26-acre (11 ha) Baker Field, which includes the Lawrence A.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Wien Stadium as well as facilities for field sports, outdoor track, and tennis.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] There is a third campus on the west bank of the Hudson River, the 157-acre (64 ha) Lamont–Doherty Earth Observatory and Earth Institute in Palisades, New York.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] A fourth is the 60-acre (24 ha) Nevis Laboratories in Irvington, New York, for the study of particle and motion physics.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] A satellite site in Paris holds classes at Reid Hall.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In 2006, the university established the Office of Environmental Stewardship to initiate, coordinate and implement programs to reduce the university's environmental footprint.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Green Building Council selected the university's Manhattanville plan for the Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design (LEED) Neighborhood Design pilot program.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Columbia has been rated "B+" by the 2011 College Sustainability Report Card for its environmental and sustainability initiatives.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Kuchler U.S. potential natural vegetation types, Columbia University would have a dominant vegetation type of Appalachian Oak (*104*) with a dominant vegetation form of Eastern Hardwood Forest (*25*).
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Columbia Transportation is the bus service of the university, operated by Academy Bus Lines.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The buses are open to all Columbia faculty, students, Dodge Fitness Center members, and anyone else who holds a Columbia ID card.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In addition, all TSC students can ride the buses.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In the New York City Subway, the ("1" train) train serves the university at 116th Street-Columbia University.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The M4, M104 and M60 buses stop on Broadway while the M11 stops on Amsterdam Avenue.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The main campus is primarily boxed off by the streets of Amsterdam Avenue, Broadway, 114th street, and 120th street, with some buildings, including Barnard College, located just outside the area.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The nearest major highway is the Henry Hudson Parkway (NY 9A) to the west of the campus.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] It is located 3.4 miles (5.5 km) south of the George Washington Bridge.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Columbia is a racially diverse school, with approximately 52% of all students identifying themselves as persons of color.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Additionally, around 50% of all undergraduates received grants from Columbia.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The college is need-blind for domestic applicants.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In April 2007, Columbia University announced a $400 million donation from media billionaire alumnus John Kluge to be used exclusively for undergraduate financial aid.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The donation is among the largest single gifts to higher education.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] However, this did not apply to international students, transfer students, visiting students, or students in the School of General Studies.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In the fall of 2010, admission to Columbia's undergraduate colleges Columbia College and the Fu Foundation School of Engineering and Applied Science (also known as SEAS or Columbia Engineering) began accepting the Common Application.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The policy change made Columbia one of the last major academic institutions and the last Ivy League university to switch to the Common Application.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Columbia University is an independent, privately supported, nonsectarian and not-for-profit institution of higher education.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Its official corporate name is Trustees of Columbia University in the City of New York.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Joint degree programs are available through Union Theological Seminary, the Jewish Theological Seminary of America, and the Juilliard School.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Teachers College and Barnard College are official faculties of the university; both colleges' presidents are deans under the university governance structure.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The Columbia University Senate includes faculty and student representatives from Teachers College and Barnard College who serve two-year terms; all senators are accorded full voting privileges regarding matters impacting the entire university.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Teachers College is an affiliated, financially independent graduate school with their own board of trustees.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Pursuant to an affiliation agreement, Columbia is given the authority to confer "degrees and diplomas" to the graduates of Teachers College.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The degrees are signed by presidents of Teachers College and Columbia University in a manner analogous to the university's other graduate schools.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Columbia's General Studies school also has joint undergraduate programs available through University College London, Sciences Po, City University of Hong Kong, Trinity College Dublin, and the Juilliard School.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The university also has several Columbia Global Centers, in Amman, Beijing, Istanbul, Mumbai, Nairobi, Paris, Rio de Janeiro, Santiago, and Tunis.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Select students can study at either the University of Oxford or the University of Cambridge for a year if approved by both Columbia and either Oxford or Cambridge.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Columbia also has a dual MA program with the Aga Khan University in London.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Columbia University was ranked 12th in the United States and tenth globally for 2023–2024 by *U.S.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In 2021, Columbia was ranked seventh in the world (sixth in the United States) by *Academic Ranking of World Universities*, sixth in the world by *U.S.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] News & World Report*, 19th in the world by *QS World University Rankings*, and 11th globally by *Times Higher Education World University Rankings*.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] It was ranked in the first tier of American research universities, along with Harvard, MIT, and Stanford, in the 2019 report from the Center for Measuring University Performance.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In 2025, Columbia was ranked 250 out of 257 top colleges in "Free Speech Rankings" by the Foundation for Individual Rights and Expression and "College Pulse", after ranking 214 of 248 in 2024 and at the bottom of 203 in 2022/2023.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In 2024 and 2025, Columbia received a D on the "Campus Antisemitism Report Card" of the Anti-Defamation League, which the advocacy organization first launched in spring 2024, in the lead-up to and in the context of campus conflict over the 2024 Columbia University pro-Palestinian campus occupations.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Columbia University has been the site of many scientific milestones, including the first nuclear fission in North America, the invention of FM radio and the laser, and key contributions to neuroscience.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Researchers at Columbia have also advanced efforts in technology, such as digital media, cellular imaging, and brain-computer interfaces.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Columbia is classified among "R1: Doctoral Universities – Very high research activity".
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Columbia scientists have been credited with about 175 new inventions in the health sciences each year.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Columbia is affiliated with many research facilities, such as the Columbia Institute for Tele-Information dedicated to telecommunications and the Goddard Institute for Space Studies, which is an astronomical observatory affiliated with NASA.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Columbia is a long-standing participant of the United States Department of Veterans Affairs Yellow Ribbon Program, allowing eligible veterans and their dependents to pursue a Columbia undergraduate degree regardless of socioeconomic status for over 70 years.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Several prestigious awards are administered by Columbia University, most notably the Pulitzer Prize and the Bancroft Prize in history.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Other prizes, which are awarded by the Graduate School of Journalism, include the Alfred I. duPont–Columbia University Award, the National Magazine Awards, the Maria Moors Cabot Prizes, the John Chancellor Award, and the Lukas Prizes, which include the J.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Anthony Lukas Book Prize and Mark Lynton History Prize.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The university also administers the Louisa Gross Horwitz Prize, which is considered an important precursor to the Nobel Prize, 55 of its 117 recipients having gone on to win either a Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine or Nobel Prize in Chemistry as of October 2024; the W.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Alden Spencer Award; the Vetlesen Prize, which is known as the Nobel Prize of geology; the Japan-U.S.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Friendship Commission Prize for the Translation of Japanese Literature, the oldest such award; the Edwin Howard Armstrong award; the Calderone Prize in public health; and the Ditson Conductor's Award.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In 2020, Columbia University's student population was 31,455 (8,842 students in undergraduate programs and 22,613 in postgraduate programs), with 45% of the student population identifying themselves as a minority.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Twenty-six percent of students at Columbia have family incomes below $60,000.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] 16% of students at Columbia receive Federal Pell Grants, which mostly go to students whose family incomes are below $40,000.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Seventeen percent of students are the first member of their family to attend a four-year college.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Columbia University is home to many fraternities, sororities, and co-educational Greek organizations.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Approximately 10–15% of undergraduate students are associated with Greek life.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Many Barnard women also join Columbia sororities.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] There has been a Greek presence on campus since the establishment in 1836 of the Delta chapter of Alpha Delta Phi.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The *Columbia Daily Spectator* is the nation's second-oldest continuously operating daily student newspaper.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] *The Blue and White* is a monthly literary magazine established in 1890 that discusses campus life and local politics.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] *Bwog*, originally an offshoot of *The Blue and White* but now fully independent, is an online campus news and entertainment source.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] *The Morningside Post* is a student-run multimedia news publication.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Columbia is home to numerous undergraduate academic publications.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The *Columbia Undergraduate Science Journal* prints original science research in its two annual publications.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Other publications include *The Columbian*, the undergraduate colleges' annually published yearbook; the *Gadfly*, a biannual journal of popular philosophy produced by undergraduates; and *Rhapsody in Blue*, an undergraduate urban studies magazine.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Professional journals published by academic departments include *Current Musicology* and *The Journal of Philosophy*.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The Graduate School of Journalism publishe*s The Bronx Beat* each spring, a bi-weekly newspaper covering the South Bronx.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In 1961, the journalism school founded the *Columbia Journalism Review*, a professional magazine which is published six times a year.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Defunct publications include the *Columbia University Forum*, a review of literature and cultural affairs for alumni.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Columbia is home to two pioneers in undergraduate campus radio broadcasting, WKCR-FM and CTV.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] A student-run radio station, WKCR broadcasts to the Tri-state area and claims to be the oldest FM radio station in the world, owing to the university's affiliation with Edwin Howard Armstrong.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The station has its studios on the second floor of Alfred Lerner Hall on the Morningside campus with its main transmitter tower at 4 Times Square in Midtown Manhattan.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Columbia Television (CTV) is the nation's second oldest student television station and the home of CTV News, a weekly live news program produced by undergraduate students.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The Philolexian Society is a literary and debating club founded in 1802, making it the oldest student group at Columbia, as well as the third oldest collegiate literary society in the country.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The society annually administers the Joyce Kilmer Memorial Bad Poetry Contest.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The Columbia Parliamentary Debate Team competes in tournaments around the country as part of the American Parliamentary Debate Association, and hosts both high school and college tournaments on Columbia's campus, as well as public debates on issues affecting the university.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The Columbia International Relations Council and Association (CIRCA), oversees Columbia's Model United Nations activities.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] CIRCA hosts college and high school Model UN conferences, hosts speakers influential in international politics to speak on campus, and trains students from underprivileged schools in New York in Model UN.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Many engineering entrepreneurs in New York City have attended Columbia.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Since 1990, graduates of Columbia have established more than 100 technology companies.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The student-run group Columbia University Organization of Rising Entrepreneurs (CORE) was founded in 1999 with an aim to foster entrepreneurship on campus.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Each year CORE hosts events, including #StartupColumbia, a conference and venture competition for $250,000, and Ignite@CU, a weekend for undergrads interested in design, engineering, and entrepreneurship.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Notable speakers include Peter Thiel, Jack Dorsey, Alexis Ohanian, Drew Houston, and Mark Cuban.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] CampusNetwork, an on-campus social networking site called Campus Network that preceded Facebook, was created and popularized by Columbia engineering student Adam Goldberg in 2003.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Mark Zuckerberg later asked Goldberg to join him in Palo Alto to work on Facebook, but Goldberg declined the offer.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The Fu Foundation School of Engineering and Applied Science offers a minor in Technical Entrepreneurship through its Center for Technology, Innovation, and Community Engagement.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] SEAS' entrepreneurship activities focus on community building initiatives in New York and worldwide, made possible through partners such as Microsoft Corporation.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Bloomberg launched the NYC Media Lab to promote innovations in New York's media industry.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Situated at the New York University Tandon School of Engineering, the lab is a consortium of Columbia University, New York University, and New York City Economic Development Corporation acting to connect companies with universities in new technology research.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The Lab is modeled after similar ones at MIT and Stanford, and was established with a $250,000 grant from the New York City Economic Development Corporation.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Established in 2003 by university president Lee C.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Bollinger, the World Leaders Forum at Columbia University provides the opportunity for students and faculty to listen to world leaders in government, religion, industry, finance, and academia.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Other speakers include President Yudhoyono of Indonesia, President Pervez Musharraf of the Islamic Republic of Pakistan, Iraq President Jalal Talabani, the 14th Dalai Lama, president of the Islamic Republic of Iran Mahmoud Ahmadinejad, financier George Soros, Mayor of New York City Michael R.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Bloomberg, President Václav Klaus of the Czech Republic, President Cristina Fernández de Kirchner of Argentina, former Secretary-General of the United Nations Kofi Annan, and Al Gore.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The Columbia University Orchestra was founded by composer Edward MacDowell in 1896, and is the oldest continually operating university orchestra in the United States.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Undergraduate student composers at Columbia may choose to become involved with Columbia New Music, which sponsors concerts of music written by undergraduate students from all of Columbia's schools.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The Notes and Keys, the oldest a cappella group at Columbia, was founded in 1909.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The Columbia Queer Alliance is the central Columbia student organization that represents the bisexual, lesbian, gay, transgender, and questioning student population.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] It is the oldest gay student organization in the world, founded as the Student Homophile League in 1967 by students including lifelong activist Stephen Donaldson.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Columbia University campus military groups include the U.S.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Military Veterans of Columbia University and Advocates for Columbia ROTC.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In the 2005–06 academic year, the Columbia Military Society, Columbia's student group for ROTC cadets and Marine officer candidates, was renamed the Hamilton Society for "students who aspire to serve their nation through the military in the tradition of Alexander Hamilton".
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Columbia has several secret societies, including St.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Anthony Hall, which was founded at the university in 1847, and two senior societies, the Nacoms and Sachems.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] A member institution of the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) in Division I FCS, Columbia fields varsity teams in 29 sports and is a member of the Ivy League.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The football Lions play home games at the 17,000-seat Robert K.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The Baker Athletics Complex also includes facilities for baseball, softball, soccer, lacrosse, field hockey, tennis, track, and rowing, as well as the new Campbell Sports Center, which opened in January 2013.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The basketball, fencing, swimming & diving, volleyball, and wrestling programs are based at the Dodge Physical Fitness Center on the main campus.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Former students include Baseball Hall of Famers Lou Gehrig and Eddie Collins, football Hall of Famer Sid Luckman, Marcellus Wiley, and world champion women's weightlifter Karyn Marshall.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] On May 17, 1939, fledgling NBC broadcast a doubleheader between the Columbia Lions and the Princeton Tigers at Columbia's Baker Field, making it the first televised regular athletic event in history.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Columbia University participated in multiple firsts within collegiate athletics.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The football program is best known for its record of futility set during the 1980s: between 1983 and 1988, the team lost 44 games in a row, which is still the record for the NCAA Football Championship Subdivision.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The streak was broken on October 8, 1988, with a 16–13 victory over arch-rival Princeton University.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] That was the Lions' first victory at Wien Stadium, which had been opened during the losing streak and was already four years old.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] A new tradition has developed with the Liberty Cup.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The Liberty Cup is awarded annually to the winner of the football game between Fordham and Columbia Universities, two of the only three NCAA Division I football teams in New York City.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The Varsity Show is one of the oldest traditions at Columbia.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Founded in 1893 as a fundraiser for the university's fledgling athletic teams, the Varsity Show now draws together the entire Columbia undergraduate community for a series of performances every April.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Dedicated to producing a unique full-length musical that skewers and satirizes many dubious aspects of life at Columbia, the Varsity Show is written and performed exclusively by university undergraduates.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Various renowned playwrights, composers, authors, directors, and actors have contributed to the Varsity Show, either as writers or performers, while students at Columbia, including Richard Rodgers, Oscar Hammerstein II, Lorenz Hart, Herman J.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Diamond, Herman Wouk, Greta Gerwig, and Kate McKinnon.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Notable past shows include *Fly With Me* (1920), *The* *Streets of New York* (1948), *The Sky's the Limit* (1954), and *Angels at Columbia* (1994).
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] In particular, *Streets of New York*, after having been revived three times, opened off-Broadway in 1963 and was awarded a 1964 Drama Desk Award.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] *The Mischief Maker* (1903), written by Edgar Allan Woolf and Cassius Freeborn, premiered at Madison Square Garden in 1906 as *Mam'zelle Champagne*.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The campus Tree Lighting ceremony was inaugurated in 1998.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] It celebrates the illumination of the medium-sized trees lining College Walk in front of Kent Hall and Hamilton Hall on the east end and Dodge Hall and Pulitzer Hall on the west, just before finals week in early December.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Students meet at the sundial for free hot chocolate, performances by *a cappella* groups, and speeches by the university president and a guest.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Immediately following the College Walk festivities is one of Columbia's older holiday traditions, the lighting of the Yule Log.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The Christmas ceremony dates to a period prior to the American Revolutionary War, but lapsed before being revived by President Nicholas Murray Butler in 1910.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] A troop of students dressed as Continental Army soldiers carry the eponymous log from the sundial to the lounge of John Jay Hall, where it is lit amid the singing of seasonal carols.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] The Christmas ceremony is accompanied by a reading of *A Visit From St.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p01] Nicholas* by Clement Clarke Moore and *Yes, Virginia, There is a Santa Claus* by Francis Pharcellus Church.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] The university has graduated many notable alumni, including five Founding Fathers of the United States, an author of the United States Constitution and a member of the Committee of Five.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Three United States presidents have attended Columbia, as well as ten justices of the Supreme Court of the United States, including three chief justices.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] As of 2011, 125 Pulitzer Prize winners and 39 Oscar winners have attended Columbia.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Columbia faculty received multiple Nobel Prizes, including Joseph Stiglitz (Economics, 2001), Richard Axel and Linda Buck (Medicine, 2004), Edmund Phelps (Economics, 2006), and Orhan Pamuk (Literature, 2006), among others.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] In a 2016 ranking of universities worldwide with respect to living graduates who are billionaires, Columbia ranked second, after Harvard.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Presidents Theodore Roosevelt and Franklin Delano Roosevelt attended the law school.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Other political figures educated at Columbia include former U.S.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] President Barack Obama, Associate Justice of the U.S.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Supreme Court Ruth Bader Ginsburg,, William O.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Douglas, Supreme Court Justice and former Chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, former U.S.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, former chairman of the U.S.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Federal Reserve Bank Alan Greenspan, U.S.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] One of the founding fathers of modern India and the prime architect of the Constitution of India, B.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Alumni of Columbia have occupied top positions in Wall Street and the rest of the business world.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Notable members of the Astor family attended Columbia, while other business graduates include investor Warren Buffett, former CEO of PBS and NBC Lawrence K.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Robson Walton, Bain Capital Co-Managing Partner, Jonathan Lavine, Thomson Reuters CEO Tom Glocer, New York Stock Exchange president Lynn Martin, and AllianceBernstein Chairman and CEO Lewis A.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] CEOs of top Fortune 500 companies include James P.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Stevens of Lockheed Martin, Philippe Dauman of Viacom, Robert Bakish of Paramount Global, Ursula Burns of Xerox, Devin Wenig of EBay, Vikram Pandit of Citigroup, Ralph Izzo of Public Service Enterprise Group, Gail Koziara Boudreaux of Anthem, and Frank Blake of The Home Depot.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Labor organizer and women's educator Louise Leonard McLaren received her degree of Master of Arts from Columbia.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Many Columbia alumni have gone on to renowned careers in the arts, including composers Richard Rodgers, Oscar Hammerstein II, Lorenz Hart, and Art Garfunkel; and painter Georgia O'Keeffe.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Five United States Poet Laureates received their degrees from Columbia.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Columbia alumni have made an indelible mark in the field of American poetry and literature, with such people as Jack Kerouac and Allen Ginsberg, pioneers of the Beat Generation; and Langston Hughes and Zora Neale Hurston, seminal figures in the Harlem Renaissance, all having attended the university.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Other notable writers who attended Columbia include authors Isaac Asimov, J.D.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Le Guin, Danielle Valore Evans, and Hunter S.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] In architecture, William Lee Stoddart, a prolific architect of U.S.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] University alumni have also been very prominent in the film industry, with 33 alumni and former students winning a combined 43 Academy Awards (as of 2011).
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Some notable Columbia alumni that have gone on to work in film include directors Sidney Lumet (*12 Angry Men*) and Kathryn Bigelow (*The Hurt Locker*), screenwriters Howard Koch (*Casablanca*) and Joseph L.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Mankiewicz (*All About Eve*), and actors James Cagney, Ed Harris and Timothée Chalamet.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Columbia University's faculty has included many notable names in the role of university president, including 34th President of the United States Dwight D.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Eisenhower, 4th Vice President of the United States George Clinton, Founding Father and U.S.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Senator from Connecticut William Samuel Johnson, Nobel Peace Prize laureate Nicholas Murray Butler, and First Amendment scholar Lee Bollinger.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Other notable Columbia University faculty include Zbigniew Brzezinski, Sonia Sotomayor, Kimberlé Crenshaw, Lee Bollinger, Franz Boas, Margaret Mead, Edward Sapir, John Dewey, Charles A.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] As of 2021, Columbia employs 4,381 faculty, including 70 members of the National Academy of Sciences, 178 members of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences, and 65 members of the National Academy of Medicine.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] In total, the Columbia faculty has included 52 Nobel laureates, 12 National Medal of Science recipients, and 32 National Academy of Engineering members.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Columbia University faculty played particularly important roles during World War II and the creation of the New Deal under President Franklin D.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Roosevelt, who attended Columbia Law School.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] The three core members of Roosevelt's Brain Trust: Adolf A.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Berle, Raymond Moley, and Rexford Tugwell, were law professors at Columbia.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Former United States Secretary of Labor, Francis Perkins was the principle architect of the New Deal and also earned her Master's from Columbia University.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] The Statistical Research Group, which used statistics to analyze military problems during World War II, was composed of Columbia researchers and faculty including George Stigler and Milton Friedman.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Columbia faculty and researchers, including Enrico Fermi, Leo Szilard, Eugene T.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Pegram, Walter Zinn, Chien-Shiung Wu, Francis G.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Anderson, and Isidor Isaac Rabi, also played a significant role during the early phases of the Manhattan Project.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Following the rise of Nazi Germany, the exiled Institute for Social Research at Goethe University Frankfurt would affiliate itself with Columbia from 1934 to 1950.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] It was during this period that thinkers including Theodor W.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Adorno, Max Horkheimer, and Herbert Marcuse wrote and published some of the most seminal works of the Frankfurt School, including *Reason and Revolution*, *Dialectic of Enlightenment*, and *Eclipse of Reason*.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Professors Edward Said, author of *Orientalism*, and Gayatri Chakravorty Spivak are generally considered as founders of the field of postcolonialism; other professors that have significantly contributed to the field include Hamid Dabashi, Rashid Khalidi, and Joseph Massad.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] The works of professors Kimberlé Crenshaw, Patricia J.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Williams, and Kendall Thomas were foundational to the field of critical race theory.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Columbia and its affiliated faculty have also made significant contributions to the study of religion.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] The affiliated Union Theological Seminary is a center of liberal Christianity in the United States, having served as the birthplace of Black theology through the efforts of faculty including James H.
[src:aaron-cicourel/columbia-university-p02] Cone and Cornel West, and Womanist theology, through the works of Katie Cannon, Emilie Townes, and Delores S.
